o games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Lasseter]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Bonnie Arnold]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joel Cohen]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Pete Docter]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Lasseter]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joe Ranft]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Alec Sokolow]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Andrew Stanton]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joss Whedon]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about dolls]]\n[[Category:1995 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "108.18.46.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCritical response)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toy_Story"}
{"title_page": "Chippenham railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Chippenham\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Chipenham station entrance 2011.jpg\n| manager      = [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]\n| code         = CPM\n| dft_category = C1\n| platforms    = 2\n| locale       = [[Chippenham, Wiltshire|Chippenham]]\n| borough      = [[Wiltshire|County of Wiltshire]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.4625|-2.1154|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- | usage0203    = {{pad}}1.151\n| usage0405    = {{increase}} 1.257\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 1.316\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 1.415\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 1.473\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 1.560\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 1.517\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 1.654\n| lowint1011   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 8,996\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 1.751\n| lowint1112   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 2,124\n| usage1213    = {{decrease}} 1.747\n| lowint1213   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 3,431\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 1.826\n| lowint1314   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 22,376 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 1.896\n| lowint1415   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 27,497\n| usage1516    = {{decrease}} 1.816\n| lowint1516   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 30,500\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 1.939\n| lowint1617   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 40,218\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 1.890\n| lowint1718   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 21,585\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 1.972\n| lowint1819   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 21,088\n| original     = [[Great Western Railway]]\n| years        = 31 May 1841\n| events       = Opened\n| caption      = The station buildings, seen from the southwest\n| owner        = [[Network Rail]]\n| gridref      = ST920737\n| pregroup     = Great Western Railway\n| postgroup    = Great Western Railway\n}}\n'''Chippenham railway station''' is on the [[Great Western Main Line]] (GWML) in [[South West England]], serving the town of [[Chippenham]], Wiltshire. It is {{convert|93|mi|76|chain|km}} down the line from {{stn|London Paddington}} and is situated between {{rws|Swindon}} and {{rws|Bath Spa}} on the GWML. The [[Wessex Main Line]] diverges from the GWML to the southwest of Chippenham and runs to {{rws|Trowbridge}} via {{rws|Melksham}}.\n\nIt is managed by [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]], which also operates all the trains that call.\n\nOnly two platforms at the station remain in use; the platform by the main entrance is now disused.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chippenham station entrance geograph-3148842-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Station entrance (1989)]]\nThe main line of the [[Great Western Railway]] (GWR) was authorised in 1835, and opened in stages:<ref>{{cite book |last=MacDermot |first=E.T. |title=History of the Great Western Railway, vol. I: 1833\u20131863 |year=1927 |publisher=[[Great Western Railway]] |location=Paddington |page=25 |ref=harv }}</ref> the section from {{stnlnk|Hay Lane}} westward to Chippenham opened on 31 May 1841.<ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=124}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=60 |ref=harv }}</ref> The final section of the line, between Chippenham and [[Bath Spa railway station|Bath]], opened on 30 June 1841.<ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=131}}</ref>\n\nChippenham was soon served by other lines. The [[Wilts, Somerset and Weymouth Railway]] (WS&WR) was authorised in 1845 and the first section opened on 5 September 1848; this ran from Thingley Junction, west of Chippenham, to {{stnlnk|Westbury}}, and the WS&WR was absorbed by the GWR in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |last=Awdry |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Awdry |title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies |year=1990 |publisher=Guild Publishing |location=London |id=CN 8983 |page=52 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=286}}</ref> The [[Calne Railway]] was authorised in 1860 and opened on 3 November 1863; this company remained independent for some years, until absorbed by the GWR in 1892.<ref>{{cite book |last=MacDermot |first=E.T. |title=History of the Great Western Railway, vol. II: 1863\u20131921 |year=1931 |publisher=[[Great Western Railway]] |location=Paddington |oclc=55853736 |page=6 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Awdry|1990|p=20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1858 the station was expanded and gained a goods shed and an engine shed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daniel|first1=John|title=A Selection of Great Western Stations|url=http://www.greatwestern.org.uk/stat_2.htm|website=The Great Western Archive|accessdate=25 February 2015|at=Chippenham|date=April 2013}}</ref> A railway connection was laid to Chippenham Gas Works in 1906; this connection closed in 1932. Chippenham engine shed closed in March 1964 and services on the Calne branch ended in 1965. Chippenham East and West signal boxes closed on 21 August 1966. As from 1 February 1976 the original down platform was taken out of use and services travelling west used the south side of the island platform.<ref name=transwilts>{{cite web|url=http://www.twcrp.org.uk/about.html|title=The \"TransWilts\" \u2013 Some key facts|last=TransWilts Community Rail Partnership|year=2009|publisher=Self|accessdate=4 June 2012|location=Melksham, Wilts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121045908/http://www.twcrp.org.uk/about.html|archive-date=21 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Station Masters===\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Jonathan Carthew Hornblower ca. 1859\u20131889<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Primrose League |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000360/18890502/049/0008 |newspaper=Devizes and Wiltshire Gazette |location=England |date=2 May 1889 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*H.E. Williams 1889\u20131895 (afterwards station master at Newton Abbot)\n*Thomas Albert Williams 1895<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The New Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/18950119/128/0005 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=19 January 1895 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \u2013 1896 (formerly station master at Hayle)\n*John Phillips 1897\u20131920\n*E.C. Beard 1920\u20131925<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Station Master Retiring |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/19250110/050/0003 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=10 January 1925 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (formerly station master at Melksham)\n*G.R. Halford 1925\u20131933<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Yatton Man to be Stationmaster at Chippenham |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000513/19330303/115/0009 |newspaper=Western Daily Press |location=England |date=3 March 1933 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*William Folland 1933\u20131935<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/19350504/194/0008 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=4 May 1935 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*G.E. Nailor 1935\u20131938\n*Frank Gale 1938\u20131944<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000515/19441125/055/0010 |newspaper=Bath Chronicle and Weekly Gazette |location=England |date=25 November 1944 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Bath)\n*R.W. Best ca. 1949\n{{div col end}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Description==\nThe original station building at Chippenham was built to [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]]'s design and opened in 1841.<ref>{{cite book|title=Brunel's Britain|first=Derrick |last= Beckett|publisher=David & Charles|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7153-2360-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/brunelsbritain0000beck_o9n7/page/62 62]| url = https://archive.org/details/brunelsbritain0000beck_o9n7|url-access=registration}}</ref> With the subsequent opening of new lines to {{Stnlnk|Salisbury}} and {{Stnlnk|Weymouth}}, the station was not adequate to meet the increased demand and was redesigned by J H Bertram in 1856 to 1858; it is a grade II [[listed building]], constructed in [[Bath Stone]] [[ashlar]] with a bay window at one end and a wing at the other making a long, low composition.<ref>{{cite book |last=Clark |first=R H |title=An Historic Survey of Selected Great Western Stations, volume 3 |year=1981}}</ref>\n\nIn the station yard, there is another grade II listed building partly in random stone but mainly weather-boarded on a timber frame with a pitched slate roof. It is an early weighbridge house and coal merchant's office dating to around 1840.\n[[File:Chippenham station geograph-3148835-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Platform view in 1989]]\n\nImmediately west of the station lies the grade II listed Chippenham [[viaduct]] designed by Brunel in 1841. The first arch, over New Road, appears to have been modelled on the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[triumphal arch]]. It has a {{convert|26|ft|0|sing=on}} span and is flanked by two smaller pedestrian arches of {{convert|10|ft|0}}. All is surmounted by a heavy cornice and parapet. The north side is constructed from Bath Stone ashlar with some brick patching, while the south side is in blue brick following widening in the early 1900s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Biddle |first=Gordon |title=Britain's Historic Railway Buildings: an Oxford Gazetteer of Structures and Sites |year=2003 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-866247-1}}</ref>\n\nPlatform 1 is used for westbound [[Great Western Main Line]] services towards Bristol Temple Meads, the West Country, South Wales and is also used for [[Wessex Main Line]] services towards Southampton Central. Platform 2 is used for eastbound services towards London Paddington and Cheltenham Spa. On the disused platform there is cycle storage, a seating area and a caf\u00e9.<ref name=transwilts/>\n\nThere are two footbridges at the station, although until 2016 one only carried a right of way over the railway. This bridge was replaced with a new one providing steps and lifts on both platforms, opening in January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/aspx/6374.aspx|title=Timeline: Access for All stations list|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/11764760.115_year_old_railway_bridge_comes_down_as_part_of___3m_access_scheme/|title=115-year-old railway bridge comes down as part of \u00a33m access scheme|last=Armstrong|first=Julie|date=2 February 2015|website=Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/resources/opening-of-chippenham-stations-new-footbridge-and-lifts|title=Opening of Chippenham station's new footbridge and lifts|last=|first=|date=22 January 2016|website=Network Rail|language=en|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref>This work was funded under the Department for Transport's Access for All scheme, although the bridge required replacement as part of the project to electrify the Great Western Main Line, as it was too low for the overhead wires to fit underneath. The footbridge was closed for 2 weeks in September 2016, eight months after opening, due to drainage issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/14709377.new-railway-station-bridge-in-3m-revamp-needs-work-after-just-8-months/|title=New railway station bridge in \u00a33m revamp needs work after just 8 months|website=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> It has also been criticised as no lift is provided to the car park to the north of the station, although passive provision was made for its installation in the future.\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2004, the station received an award to recognise its safety and security. The award, which lasted for two years, followed a passenger survey which found that 98% of the passengers through Chippenham said they felt 'safe' or 'very safe' whilst on the premises. The station is monitored by 24-hour [[CCTV]] and is [[Burglar alarm|alarmed]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://fgw.2020apps.co.uk/NewsItem.aspx?id=187 |title=Chippenham railway station receives national award for security |publisher=First Great Western |date=21 December 2004 |accessdate=4 June 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n[[File:Chippenham - FGW 43140 down train.jpg|thumb|A First Great Western service from London Paddington]]\nThe station has frequent eastbound services to {{stnlnk|London Paddington}}; and westbound services to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol]] and [[Bath Spa railway station|Bath]],  with some extensions to [[Devon]], [[Taunton]], and [[South Wales]]. Currently, these trains run every half an hour in both directions and extensions to stations further afield westbound are made regularly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstgreatwestern.railsaver.co.uk/firstgreatwestern.htm |title=First Great Western Trains |at=Services near the bottom |accessdate=11 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227032055/http://www.firstgreatwestern.railsaver.co.uk/firstgreatwestern.htm |archive-date=27 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe \"TransWilts\" line from Swindon via Chippenham to {{rws|Melksham}}, {{rws|Trowbridge}} and {{rws|Westbury}} has  trains every two hours each way on weekdays and six each way on Sundays.  Two southbound weekday trains continue through to {{rws|Southampton Central}}, and two in the other direction to {{rws|Cheltenham Spa}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.twcrp.org.uk/timetable.html|title=Trains from Swindon via Chippenham Melksham and Trowbridge to Westbury|website=TransWilts Community Rail Partnership|access-date=17 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913044730/http://www.twcrp.org.uk/timetable.html|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nChippenham station connects to the [[Wessex Main Line]] via Melksham.\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line two to one |next={{rws|Swindon}} |previous1={{rws|Bath Spa}} |route1=[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]<br /><small> [[Great Western Main Line|London \u2013 Bristol]] </small> |col1={{FGW colour}} |previous2={{rws|Melksham}} |route2=[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]<br /><small> [[Wessex Main Line]] </small> |col2={{FGW colour}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line|previous={{stnlnk|Corsham}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>|next={{stnlnk|Christian Malford Halt}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>|route=[[Great Western Railway]]<br /><small>[[Great Western Main Line]]</small> |col={{GWR colour}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line|previous=|next={{Stnlnk|Stanley Bridge Halt}}|route=BR (Western Region)<br /><small>[[Chippenham and Calne Line]]</small> |col={{BR(W) colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Future==\n{{main|21st Century modernisation of the Great Western Main Line}}\nThere are plans to [[Electrify (rail)|electrify]] the Great Western Main Line, originally for completion by 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Network_Specification_Western.aspx#map-9|title=Network Specification 2011 \u2013 Western|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref> but delayed until at least 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/gwml-electrification-dates-revealed|title=GWML electrification dates revealed|last=|first=|date=22 January 2016|website=Railway Technology Magazine|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrain operator [[Go-Op (train operating company)|Go-Op]] included Chippenham in its 2016 and 2019 plans for a service from the west of England to the West Midlands, via Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.go-op.coop/train/|title=Proposed route|last=|first=|date=|website=GO-OP|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.frometimes.co.uk/2019/03/26/rail-travel-boost-for-frome/|title=Rail travel boost for Frome|date=26 March 2019|website=Frome Times|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Chippenham Station Hub project aims to increase parking provision and improve the area around the station by building multi-storey car parks, releasing land for development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swlep.co.uk/projects/project-detail/chippenham-station|title=Chippenham Station|website=SWLEP|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> There are seven phases, with Phase 1, the refurbishment of the booking ofice, having been completed and Phase 2 (redevelopment of Sadler's Mead car park) being in progress as of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wiltshire.gov.uk/news/articles/chippenham-station-consultation|title=News - Chippenham railway consultation - News - Wiltshire Council|website=wiltshire.gov.uk|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wiltshire.gov.uk/news/articles/work-on-improvements-for-chippenham-car-park-start-this-week|title=News - Work on improvements for Chippenham Car Park start this week - News - Wiltshire Council|website=wiltshire.gov.uk|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Engineering works==\nNorthwest of the station is an engineering works, established on a smaller site north of the station in 1842 by [[Rowland Brotherhood]] to support the [[Great Western Railway]], and later supplying equipment to the worldwide rail industry. From 1894 it was home to the company which in 1935 became [[Westinghouse Brake and Signal Company Ltd|Westinghouse Brake and Signal]], manufacturers of [[Railway air brake|railway air braking]] and [[Railway signalling|signalling]] equipment. Westinghouse was acquired by [[Hawker Siddeley]] in 1979, then sold to [[BTR plc|BTR]] in 1992. After BTR merged with Siebe to form [[Invensys]], Westinghouse Brakes was sold in 2000 to [[Knorr-Bremse]], who opened a new factory at [[Bowerhill]], Melksham.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.polunnio.co.uk/current-publications/|title=A Hundred Years of Speed with Safety: The Inception and Progress of the Westinghouse Brake & Signal Company Ltd., 1881 \u2013 1981|publisher=Hobnob Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-946418-51-0|author=O.S. Nock}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.invensys-investor.com/isys/news/2000/2000-04-25/|title=Invensys Sells Westinghouse Brakes to Knorr-Bremse|date=25 April 2000|website=Invensys|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060314205854/http://www.invensys-investor.com/isys/news/2000/2000-04-25/|archive-date=14 March 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe signals business remained at Chippenham and became [[Westinghouse Rail Systems]], within [[Invensys Rail Group]]. This business was sold to [[Siemens]] in 2013 and became part of Siemens Rail Automation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/siemens-completes-invensys-rail-acquisition.html|title=Siemens completes Invensys Rail acquisition|date=2 May 2013|newspaper=Railway Gazette|access-date=19 February 2017|work=|language=en}}</ref> Proposals submitted in 2016 for redevelopment of the site include homes, shops and a hotel as well as business space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/14461100.Plans_submitted_to_redevelop_Langley_Park/|title=Plans submitted to redevelop Langley Park|last=Mackley|first=Stefan|date=29 April 2016|website=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|access-date=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wiltshire railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Great Western Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1841]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Great Western Railway]]\n[[Category:Former Great Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Chippenham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| name         = Chippenham\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Chipenham station entrance 2011.jpg\n| manager      = [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]\n| code         = CPM\n| dft_category = C1\n| platforms    = 2\n| locale       = [[Chippenham, Wiltshire|Chippenham]]\n| borough      = [[Wiltshire|County of Wiltshire]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.4625|-2.1154|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- | usage0203    = {{pad}}1.151\n| usage0405    = {{increase}} 1.257\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 1.316\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 1.415\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 1.473\n| usage0809    = {{increase}} 1.560\n| usage0910    = {{decrease}} 1.517\n| usage1011    = {{increase}} 1.654\n| lowint1011   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 8,996\n| usage1112    = {{increase}} 1.751\n| lowint1112   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 2,124\n| usage1213    = {{decrease}} 1.747\n| lowint1213   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 3,431\n| usage1314    = {{increase}} 1.826\n| lowint1314   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 22,376 -->\n| usage1415    = {{increase}} 1.896\n| lowint1415   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 27,497\n| usage1516    = {{decrease}} 1.816\n| lowint1516   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 30,500\n| usage1617    = {{increase}} 1.939\n| lowint1617   = {{pad|1em}}{{increase}} 40,218\n| usage1718    = {{decrease}} 1.890\n| lowint1718   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 21,585\n| usage1819    = {{increase}} 1.972\n| lowint1819   = {{pad|1em}}{{decrease}} 21,088\n| original     = [[Great Western Railway]]\n| years        = 31 May 1841\n| events       = Opened\n| caption      = The station buildings, seen from the southwest\n| owner        = [[Network Rail]]\n| gridref      = ST920737\n| pregroup     = Great Western Railway\n| postgroup    = Great Western Railway\n}}\n'''Chippenham railway station''' is on the [[Great Western Main Line]] (GWML) in [[South West England]], serving the town of [[Chippenham]], Wiltshire. It is {{convert|93|mi|76|chain|km}} down the line from {{stn|London Paddington}} and is situated between {{rws|Swindon}} and {{rws|Bath Spa}} on the GWML. The [[Wessex Main Line]] diverges from the GWML to the southwest of Chippenham and runs to {{rws|Trowbridge}} via {{rws|Melksham}}.\n\nIt is managed by [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]], which also operates all the trains that call.\n\nOnly two platforms at the station remain in use; the platform by the main entrance is now disused.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chippenham station entrance geograph-3148842-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Station entrance (1989)]]\nThe main line of the [[Great Western Railway]] (GWR) was authorised in 1835, and opened in stages:<ref>{{cite book |last=MacDermot |first=E.T. |title=History of the Great Western Railway, vol. I: 1833\u20131863 |year=1927 |publisher=[[Great Western Railway]] |location=Paddington |page=25 |ref=harv }}</ref> the section from {{stnlnk|Hay Lane}} westward to Chippenham opened on 31 May 1841.<ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=124}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Butt |first=R.V.J. |title=The Directory of Railway Stations |year=1995 |publisher=Patrick Stephens Ltd |location=Yeovil |isbn=1-85260-508-1 |id=R508 |page=60 |ref=harv }}</ref> The final section of the line, between Chippenham and [[Bath Spa railway station|Bath]], opened on 30 June 1841.<ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=131}}</ref>\n\nChippenham was soon served by other lines. The [[Wilts, Somerset and Weymouth Railway]] (WS&WR) was authorised in 1845 and the first section opened on 5 September 1848; this ran from Thingley Junction, west of Chippenham, to {{stnlnk|Westbury}}, and the WS&WR was absorbed by the GWR in 1851.<ref>{{cite book |last=Awdry |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Awdry |title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies |year=1990 |publisher=Guild Publishing |location=London |id=CN 8983 |page=52 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|MacDermot|1927|p=286}}</ref> The [[Calne Railway]] was authorised in 1860 and opened on 3 November 1863; this company remained independent for some years, until absorbed by the GWR in 1892.<ref>{{cite book |last=MacDermot |first=E.T. |title=History of the Great Western Railway, vol. II: 1863\u20131921 |year=1931 |publisher=[[Great Western Railway]] |location=Paddington |oclc=55853736 |page=6 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Awdry|1990|p=20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1858 the station was expanded and gained a goods shed and an engine shed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daniel|first1=John|title=A Selection of Great Western Stations|url=http://www.greatwestern.org.uk/stat_2.htm|website=The Great Western Archive|accessdate=25 February 2015|at=Chippenham|date=April 2013}}</ref> A railway connection was laid to Chippenham Gas Works in 1906; this connection closed in 1932. Chippenham engine shed closed in March 1964 and services on the Calne branch ended in 1965. Chippenham East and West signal boxes closed on 21 August 1966. As from 1 February 1976 the original down platform was taken out of use and services travelling west used the south side of the island platform.<ref name=transwilts>{{cite web|url=http://www.twcrp.org.uk/about.html|title=The \"TransWilts\" \u2013 Some key facts|last=TransWilts Community Rail Partnership|year=2009|publisher=Self|accessdate=4 June 2012|location=Melksham, Wilts|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121045908/http://www.twcrp.org.uk/about.html|archive-date=21 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Station Masters===\n\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Jonathan Carthew Hornblower ca. 1859\u20131889<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The Primrose League |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000360/18890502/049/0008 |newspaper=Devizes and Wiltshire Gazette |location=England |date=2 May 1889 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*H.E. Williams 1889\u20131895 (afterwards station master at Newton Abbot)\n*Thomas Albert Williams 1895<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=The New Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/18950119/128/0005 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=19 January 1895 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> \u2013 1896 (formerly station master at Hayle)\n*John Phillips 1897\u20131920\n*E.C. Beard 1920\u20131925<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Station Master Retiring |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/19250110/050/0003 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=10 January 1925 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (formerly station master at Melksham)\n*G.R. Halford 1925\u20131933<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Yatton Man to be Stationmaster at Chippenham |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000513/19330303/115/0009 |newspaper=Western Daily Press |location=England |date=3 March 1933 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*William Folland 1933\u20131935<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=New Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001557/19350504/194/0008 |newspaper=Wiltshire Times and Trowbridge Advertiser |location=England |date=4 May 1935 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref>\n*G.E. Nailor 1935\u20131938\n*Frank Gale 1938\u20131944<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Stationmaster |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000515/19441125/055/0010 |newspaper=Bath Chronicle and Weekly Gazette |location=England |date=25 November 1944 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=British Newspaper Archive |url-access=subscription  }}</ref> (afterwards station master at Bath)\n*R.W. Best ca. 1949\n{{div col end}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Description==\nThe original station building at Chippenham was built to [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]]'s design and opened in 1841.<ref>{{cite book|title=Brunel's Britain|first=Derrick |last= Beckett|publisher=David & Charles|year=2006|isbn=978-0-7153-2360-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/brunelsbritain0000beck_o9n7/page/62 62]| url = https://archive.org/details/brunelsbritain0000beck_o9n7|url-access=registration}}</ref> With the subsequent opening of new lines to {{Stnlnk|Salisbury}} and {{Stnlnk|Weymouth}}, the station was not adequate to meet the increased demand and was redesigned by J H Bertram in 1856 to 1858; it is a grade II [[listed building]], constructed in [[Bath Stone]] [[ashlar]] with a bay window at one end and a wing at the other making a long, low composition.<ref>{{cite book |last=Clark |first=R H |title=An Historic Survey of Selected Great Western Stations, volume 3 |year=1981}}</ref>\n\nIn the station yard, there is another grade II listed building partly in random stone but mainly weather-boarded on a timber frame with a pitched slate roof. It is an early weighbridge house and coal merchant's office dating to around 1840.\n[[File:Chippenham station geograph-3148835-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Platform view in 1989]]\n\nImmediately west of the station lies the grade II listed Chippenham [[viaduct]] designed by Brunel in 1841. The first arch, over New Road, appears to have been modelled on the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[triumphal arch]]. It has a {{convert|26|ft|0|sing=on}} span and is flanked by two smaller pedestrian arches of {{convert|10|ft|0}}. All is surmounted by a heavy cornice and parapet. The north side is constructed from Bath Stone ashlar with some brick patching, while the south side is in blue brick following widening in the early 1900s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Biddle |first=Gordon |title=Britain's Historic Railway Buildings: an Oxford Gazetteer of Structures and Sites |year=2003 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-866247-1}}</ref>\n\nPlatform 1 is used for westbound [[Great Western Main Line]] services towards Bristol Temple Meads, the West Country, South Wales and is also used for [[Wessex Main Line]] services towards Southampton Central. Platform 2 is used for eastbound services towards London Paddington and Cheltenham Spa. On the disused platform there is cycle storage, a seating area and a caf\u00e9.<ref name=transwilts/>\n\nPassenger access improvements under the 'Access for All' scheme, completed in 2016, included replacement of the western footbridge and installation of lifts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/aspx/6374.aspx|title=Timeline: Access for All stations list|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/11764760.115_year_old_railway_bridge_comes_down_as_part_of___3m_access_scheme/|title=115-year-old railway bridge comes down as part of \u00a33m access scheme|last=Armstrong|first=Julie|date=2 February 2015|website=Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/resources/opening-of-chippenham-stations-new-footbridge-and-lifts|title=Opening of Chippenham station's new footbridge and lifts|last=|first=|date=22 January 2016|website=Network Rail|language=en|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2004, the station received an award to recognise its safety and security. The award, which lasted for two years, followed a passenger survey which found that 98% of the passengers through Chippenham said they felt 'safe' or 'very safe' whilst on the premises. The station is monitored by 24-hour [[CCTV]] and is [[Burglar alarm|alarmed]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://fgw.2020apps.co.uk/NewsItem.aspx?id=187 |title=Chippenham railway station receives national award for security |publisher=First Great Western |date=21 December 2004 |accessdate=4 June 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n[[File:Chippenham - FGW 43140 down train.jpg|thumb|A First Great Western service from London Paddington]]\nThe station has frequent eastbound services to {{stnlnk|London Paddington}}; and westbound services to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station|Bristol]] and [[Bath Spa railway station|Bath]],  with some extensions to [[Devon]], [[Taunton]], and [[South Wales]]. Currently, these trains run every half an hour in both directions and extensions to stations further afield westbound are made regularly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstgreatwestern.railsaver.co.uk/firstgreatwestern.htm |title=First Great Western Trains |at=Services near the bottom |accessdate=11 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227032055/http://www.firstgreatwestern.railsaver.co.uk/firstgreatwestern.htm |archive-date=27 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe \"TransWilts\" line from Swindon via Chippenham to {{rws|Melksham}}, {{rws|Trowbridge}} and {{rws|Westbury}} has  trains every two hours each way on weekdays and six each way on Sundays.  Two southbound weekday trains continue through to {{rws|Southampton Central}}, and two in the other direction to {{rws|Cheltenham Spa}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.twcrp.org.uk/timetable.html|title=Trains from Swindon via Chippenham Melksham and Trowbridge to Westbury|website=TransWilts Community Rail Partnership|access-date=17 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913044730/http://www.twcrp.org.uk/timetable.html|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nChippenham station connects to the [[Wessex Main Line]] via Melksham.\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line two to one |next={{rws|Swindon}} |previous1={{rws|Bath Spa}} |route1=[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]<br /><small> [[Great Western Main Line|London \u2013 Bristol]] </small> |col1={{FGW colour}} |previous2={{rws|Melksham}} |route2=[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]<br /><small> [[Wessex Main Line]] </small> |col2={{FGW colour}} }}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line|previous={{stnlnk|Corsham}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>|next={{stnlnk|Christian Malford Halt}}<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small>|route=[[Great Western Railway]]<br /><small>[[Great Western Main Line]]</small> |col={{GWR colour}} }}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{rail line|previous=|next={{Stnlnk|Stanley Bridge Halt}}|route=BR (Western Region)<br /><small>[[Chippenham and Calne Line]]</small> |col={{BR(W) colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Future==\n{{main|21st Century modernisation of the Great Western Main Line}}\nThere are plans to [[Electrify (rail)|electrify]] the Great Western Main Line, originally for completion by 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/Network_Specification_Western.aspx#map-9|title=Network Specification 2011 \u2013 Western|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=26 February 2012}}</ref> but delayed until at least 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/gwml-electrification-dates-revealed|title=GWML electrification dates revealed|last=|first=|date=22 January 2016|website=Railway Technology Magazine|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrain operator [[Go-Op (train operating company)|Go-Op]] included Chippenham in its 2016 and 2019 plans for a service from the west of England to the West Midlands, via Oxford.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.go-op.coop/train/|title=Proposed route|last=|first=|date=|website=GO-OP|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.frometimes.co.uk/2019/03/26/rail-travel-boost-for-frome/|title=Rail travel boost for Frome|date=26 March 2019|website=Frome Times|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\n==Engineering works==\nNorthwest of the station is an engineering works, established on a smaller site north of the station in 1842 by [[Rowland Brotherhood]] to support the [[Great Western Railway]], and later supplying equipment to the worldwide rail industry. From 1894 it was home to the company which in 1935 became [[Westinghouse Brake and Signal Company Ltd|Westinghouse Brake and Signal]], manufacturers of [[Railway air brake|railway air braking]] and [[Railway signalling|signalling]] equipment. Westinghouse was acquired by [[Hawker Siddeley]] in 1979, then sold to [[BTR plc|BTR]] in 1992. After BTR merged with Siebe to form [[Invensys]], Westinghouse Brakes was sold in 2000 to [[Knorr-Bremse]], who opened a new factory at [[Bowerhill]], Melksham.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.polunnio.co.uk/current-publications/|title=A Hundred Years of Speed with Safety: The Inception and Progress of the Westinghouse Brake & Signal Company Ltd., 1881 \u2013 1981|publisher=Hobnob Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0-946418-51-0|author=O.S. Nock}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.invensys-investor.com/isys/news/2000/2000-04-25/|title=Invensys Sells Westinghouse Brakes to Knorr-Bremse|date=25 April 2000|website=Invensys|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060314205854/http://www.invensys-investor.com/isys/news/2000/2000-04-25/|archive-date=14 March 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe signals business remained at Chippenham and became [[Westinghouse Rail Systems]], within [[Invensys Rail Group]]. This business was sold to [[Siemens]] in 2013 and became part of Siemens Rail Automation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/siemens-completes-invensys-rail-acquisition.html|title=Siemens completes Invensys Rail acquisition|date=2 May 2013|newspaper=Railway Gazette|access-date=19 February 2017|work=|language=en}}</ref> Proposals submitted in 2016 for redevelopment of the site include homes, shops and a hotel as well as business space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/14461100.Plans_submitted_to_redevelop_Langley_Park/|title=Plans submitted to redevelop Langley Park|last=Mackley|first=Stefan|date=29 April 2016|website=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald|language=en|access-date=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wiltshire railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Great Western Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1841]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by Great Western Railway]]\n[[Category:Former Great Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Chippenham]]\n", "name_user": "Clownfish01", "label": "safe", "comment": "More detail provided about new footbridge, and Chippenham Station Hub project added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chippenham_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Einar Gundersen", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian footballer}}\n{{for|the Norwegian Olympic wrestler|Einar Gundersen (wrestler)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Einar Gundersen\n| image = Einar \"Jeja\" Gundersen (1896 - 1962) (14364216178) (cropped).jpg\n| fullname = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1896|9|20|df=y}}\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1962|10|29|1896|9|20|df=y}}\n| height = <!--{{height|m=}}-->\n| position = \n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1= \n| youthclubs1= \n| years1=| years2 =  \n| clubs1 = [[Odd Grenland|Odd]] | clubs2 = \n| caps1= | goals1 = | caps2 = | goals2 =\n| nationalyears1= 1917\u20131928\n| nationalteam1= [[Norway national football team|Norway]]\n| nationalcaps1= 33 | nationalgoals1 = 26\n}}\n'''Einar \"Jeja\" Gundersen''' (20 September 1896 \u2013 29 October 1962) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]]. He was a centre-forward for [[Odd Grenland|Odd]], and is regarded as one of Norwegian football's first star players. He played 33 internationals for [[Norway national football team|Norway]],<ref>http://www.home.no/greenriver/players/jeja.html</ref> and his 26 international goals puts him second on the national team's all-time scoring list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/noo-recintlp.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504194906/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/noo-recintlp.html |archivedate=4 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHis nickname Jeja means literally \"Me Then\", as that was what he wondered as a kid when he wasn't picked for the team.\n\nAt club level, Gundersen scored more than 200 goals. He won the [[Norwegian football cup|Norwegian Cup]] five times. He was also a member of the Norwegian team that played in the [[1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Olympics]], and scored twice in the 3-1 win against [[England national football team|England]]'s amateur side.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Norway Squad 1920 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gundersen, Einar}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norway international footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Odds BK players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Norwegian Olympic wrestler|Einar Gundersen (wrestler)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Einar Gundersen\n| image = Einar \"Jeja\" Gundersen (1896 - 1962) (14364216178) (cropped).jpg\n| fullname = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1896|9|20|df=y}}\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1962|10|29|1896|9|20|df=y}}\n| height = <!--{{height|m=}}-->\n| position = \n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1= \n| youthclubs1= \n| years1=| years2 =  \n| clubs1 = [[Odd Grenland|Odd]] | clubs2 = \n| caps1= | goals1 = | caps2 = | goals2 =\n| nationalyears1= 1917\u20131928\n| nationalteam1= [[Norway national football team|Norway]]\n| nationalcaps1= 33 | nationalgoals1 = 26\n}}\n'''Einar \"Jeja\" Gundersen''' (20 September 1896 \u2013 29 October 1962) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]]. He was a centre-forward for [[Odd Grenland|Odd]], and is regarded as one of Norwegian football's first star players. He played 33 internationals for [[Norway national football team|Norway]],<ref>http://www.home.no/greenriver/players/jeja.html</ref> and his 26 international goals puts him second on the national team's all-time scoring list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/noo-recintlp.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504194906/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/noo-recintlp.html |archivedate=4 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHis nickname Jeja means literally \"Me Then\", as that was what he wondered as a kid when he wasn't picked for the team.\n\nAt club level, Gundersen scored more than 200 goals. He won the [[Norwegian football cup|Norwegian Cup]] five times. He was also a member of the Norwegian team that played in the [[1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Olympics]], and scored twice in the 3-1 win against [[England national football team|England]]'s amateur side.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Norway Squad 1920 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gundersen, Einar}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norway international footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Odds BK players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Norwegian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Norwegian footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einar_Gundersen"}
{"title_page": "Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda\n| image       = Tor-\u00f8yvind-hovda-hbk.jpg\n| fullname    = Tor \u00d8yvind Stens\u00e6ter Hovda\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1989|09|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ringerike (municipality)|Ringerike]], [[Norway]]\n| height      = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| clubnumber  = 7\n| years1 = 2007\u20132013 \n| clubs1 = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| caps1  = 127 \n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015     \n| clubs2 = [[Kalmar FF|Kalmar]]\n| caps2  = 25  \n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2015\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[\u00c5tvidabergs FF]] (loan) \n| caps3 = 20\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs4 = [[Sarpsborg 08 FF|Sarpsborg 08]]\n| caps4 = 26\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs5 = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| caps5 = 33\n| goals5 = 3\n| club-update = 15 September 2019\n}}\n\n'''Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda''' (born 24 September 1989 in [[Ringerike (municipality)|Ringerike]]) is a Norwegian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]]  as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda klar for Sarpsborg 08 |url=http://www.sa.no/sarpsborg-08/fotball/sport/tor-oyvind-hovda-klar-for-sarpsborg-08/s/5-46-139273|publisher=sa.no|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nHovda played youth football for both Heradsbygda IL and later [[H\u00f8nefoss BK]], where he made his first senior appearance in 2007. [[Allsvenskan]] club [[Kalmar FF]] signed Hovda for the [[2014 Allsvenskan|2014 season]], and he scored the first goal on 27 October against [[Mj\u00e4llby AIF]]. He plays most of the games in the central midfield.\n\n==Honours==\n'''H\u00f8nefoss BK'''\n*[[Norwegian First Division|1. Division]]: [[2011 Norwegian First Division|2011]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|tor-oyvind-hovda/37880}}\n\n{{Sarpsborg 08 FF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hovda, Tor Oyvind}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Kalmar FF players]]\n[[Category:Eliteserien players]]\n[[Category:Sarpsborg 08 FF players]]\n[[Category:\u00c5tvidabergs FF players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda\n| image       = Tor-\u00f8yvind-hovda-hbk.jpg\n| fullname    = Tor \u00d8yvind Stens\u00e6ter Hovda\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1989|09|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ringerike (municipality)|Ringerike]], [[Norway]]\n| height      = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| clubnumber  = 7\n| years1 = 2007\u20132013 \n| clubs1 = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| caps1  = 127 \n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2014\u20132015     \n| clubs2 = [[Kalmar FF|Kalmar]]\n| caps2  = 25  \n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2015\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[\u00c5tvidabergs FF]] (loan) \n| caps3 = 20\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs4 = [[Sarpsborg 08 FF|Sarpsborg 08]]\n| caps4 = 26\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs5 = [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]] \n| caps5 = 33\n| goals5 = 3\n| club-update = 15 September 2019\n}}\n\n'''Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda''' (born 24 September 1989 in [[Ringerike (municipality)|Ringerike]]) is a Norwegian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[H\u00f8nefoss BK|H\u00f8nefoss]]  as a [[midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tor \u00d8yvind Hovda klar for Sarpsborg 08 |url=http://www.sa.no/sarpsborg-08/fotball/sport/tor-oyvind-hovda-klar-for-sarpsborg-08/s/5-46-139273|publisher=sa.no|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nHovda played youth football for both Heradsbygda IL and later [[H\u00f8nefoss BK]], where he made his first senior appearance in 2007. [[Allsvenskan]] club [[Kalmar FF]] signed Hovda for the [[2014 Allsvenskan|2014 season]], and he scored the first goal on 27 October against [[Mj\u00e4llby AIF]]. He plays most of the games in the central midfield.\n\n==Honours==\n'''H\u00f8nefoss BK'''\n*[[Norwegian First Division|1. Division]]: [[2011 Norwegian First Division|2011]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway|tor-oyvind-hovda/37880}}\n\n{{Sarpsborg 08 FF squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hovda, Tor Oyvind}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Kalmar FF players]]\n[[Category:Eliteserien players]]\n[[Category:Sarpsborg 08 FF players]]\n[[Category:\u00c5tvidabergs FF players]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Norwegian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tor_%C3%98yvind_Hovda"}
{"title_page": "2017 in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2017}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2017]] in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]] {{small|(until 31 August)}}, [[J. Y. Pillay]] {{small|(Acting) (1 to 14 September)}}, [[Halimah Yacob]] {{small|(starting 14 September)}}\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n* 1 January \u2013 \n**The collection of iris images starts as amendments to the National Registration Act come into force. Some SingPost employees are appointed for that role.<ref>{{cite web |title=Authorities to collect iris scans from Singaporeans, PRs starting Jan 1 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/authorities-to-collect-iris-scans-from-singaporeans-prs-starting-7657104 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n**The re-registration of [[National Registration Identity Card|NRICs]] starts for those aged 55 and above.<ref>{{cite web | first1=Samantha | last1=Boh | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/nric-re-registration-for-singapore-citizens-and-prs-turning-55-years-old-from-2017 | title=NRIC re-registration for Singapore citizens and PRs turning 55 years old from 2017 | date=14 November 2016 | accessdate=27 December 2019 | website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n* 4 January \u2013 Raffles Country Club will be acquired for the [[Kuala Lumpur-Singapore High Speed Rail]] and [[Cross Island MRT line]] Western Depot, making it the second country club affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/raffles-country-club-to-make-way-for-kl-singapore-high-speed-rai-7537076 |title=Raffles Country Club to make way for KL-Singapore High-Speed Rail |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=4 January 2017 |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 5 January \u2013 [[Maxwell Chambers]] will be expanded to meet demand for [[dispute resolution]] services,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Khew |first1=Carolyn |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maxwell-chambers-to-expand-will-take-over-building-that-houses-red-dot-design |title=Maxwell Chambers to expand, will take over building that houses Red Dot Design Museum |date=5 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref> taking over the [[Red Dot|Red Dot Design Museum]], which moved to [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]] in end-2017.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/red-dot-design-museum-moving-to-marina-bay|title=Red Dot Design Museum moving to Marina Bay |date=21 June 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> The expanded section is now called [[Maxwell Chambers#Maxwell Chambers Suites|Maxwell Chambers Suites]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Prisca |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/red-dot-traffic-building-renamed-maxwell-chambers-suites |title=Red Dot Traffic Building renamed Maxwell Chambers Suites |date=22 June 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Due to strong demand, a second annexe block of 3,500 sq ft space is also constructed on top of the original 120,000 sq ft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/keynote-address-by-ms-indranee-rajah--senior-minister-of-state--.html |title=Ground-Breaking of 28 Maxwell Road |date=22 June 2017 |website=MinLaw |access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 9 January \u2013 The re-employment age is raised to the age of 67 on 1 July, from 65 currently among changes to the Retirement and Re-employment Act passed. In addition, eligible employees can be re-employed by another firm, and an option to cut 10 percent of wages at age 60 is removed.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Linette |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/higher-re-employment-age-passed-into-law-in-singapore-7533148 |title=Higher re-employment age passed into law in Singapore |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=9 January 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 10 January \u2013 The [[Active Mobility Act]] is passed to regulate [[personal transporter|personal mobility devices]] and [[bicycles]], and sets out penalties for non-compliance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-cycling-and-personal-mobility-devices-essential-to-countrys-car-lite-drive-says |title=Parliament: Cycling and personal mobility devices essential to country's car-lite drive, says Josephine Teo |date=10 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 18 January \u2013 \n**A [[NEWater]] plant is launched in Changi, built on top of an existing one.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-launches-fifth-newater-plant-at-changi-boosting-treated-used-water-supply-by-10 |title=Singapore launches fifth Newater plant at Changi, boosting water supply |date=18 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n**The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced that the current six healthcare clusters will be merged into three, namely the [[National Healthcare Group]], [[SingHealth]] and [[National University Health System]]. In addition, the National University Health System will form the National University Polyclinics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Poon |first1=Chian Hui |title=Public healthcare sector to be reorganised into 3 integrated clusters, new polyclinic group to be formed |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/public-healthcare-sector-to-be-reorganised-into-3-integrated-clusters-new |accessdate=7 July 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n* 20 January - The sleeper replacement project on the [[North South MRT line|North South]] and [[East West MRT line|East West]] lines are completed, resulting in longer lasting concrete sleepers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loh |first1=Chuan Junn |title=SMRT sleeper replacement complete, speed limits to be lifted |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/smrt-sleeper-replacement-complete-speed-limits-to-be-lifted-7571200 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028130140/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/smrt-sleeper-replacement-complete-speed-limits-to-be-lifted-7571200 |archive-date=28 October 2017 |accessdate=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 21 January \u2013 The launch of homegrown bike sharing firm [[oBike]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-sharing-system-gets-rolling |title=New bike-sharing system gets rolling |last=Cheong |first=Danson |date=21 January 2017 |website=The Straits Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810212155/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-sharing-system-gets-rolling |archive-date=10 August 2017 |url-status=live |language=en |access-date=10 August 2017 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since then, [[Ofo (bike sharing)|Ofo]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cheong |first1=Danson |title=New bike-share scheme hits the road |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-bike-share-scheme-hits-the-road |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 February 2017}}</ref> [[Mobike]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Chinese firm Mobike rolls into Singapore's bike-sharing market |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/chinese-firm-mobike-rolls-into-singapore-s-bike-sharing-market-8581486 |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=22 March 2017}}</ref> SG Bike,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hong |first1=Jose |title=Newly launched bike-sharing firm SG Bike plans to take aim at indiscriminate parking |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/newly-launched-bike-sharing-company-aims-to-target-indiscriminate-parking |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=24 August 2017}}</ref> GBikes<ref>{{cite news |title=New entrant GBikes to share 3,000 bicycles |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/new-entrant-gbikes-to-share-3000-bicycles |accessdate=10 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=18 September 2017}}</ref> and other providers have launched in the following months, leading to the scrapping of the proposed national bike sharing scheme.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plans-for-national-bike-sharing-scheme-scrapped-as-presence-of-companies-providing-such |title=Plans for national bike sharing scheme scrapped as presence of companies providing such services increases |date=24 March 2017 |website=The Straits Times |archive-date=25 January 2019 |access-date=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020301/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plans-for-national-bike-sharing-scheme-scrapped-as-presence-of-companies-providing-such |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 24 January - The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] announced that all nine [[Terrex ICV|Terrexes]] will return to Singapore after being detained in Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web |title=Detained Terrexes to return to Singapore: MFA |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/detained-terrexes-to-return-to-singapore-mfa-7556798 |accessdate=15 September 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=24 January 2017}}</ref> The vehicles arrived back in Singapore on 30 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=SAF Terrex vehicles arrive in Singapore after being detained in Hong Kong |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/saf-terrex-vehicles-arrive-in-singapore-after-being-detained-in--7550656 |accessdate=15 September 2019 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n* 6 February \u2013 Laws are passed to ban short-term [[renting]] services such as [[Airbnb]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/parliament-short-term-home-rental-illegal-under-new-law|title=Parliament: Short term home rental illegal under new law|date=2017-02-06|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n* 9 February \u2013 The Committee of Future Economy releases its report, highlighting seven strategies to transform Singapore's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/committee-on-the-future-economy-outlines-7-strategies-to-take-singapore-forward|title=Committee on the Future Economy outlines 7 strategies to take Singapore forward|last=hermesauto|date=2017-02-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019134721/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/committee-on-the-future-economy-outlines-7-strategies-to-take-singapore-forward|archive-date=2018-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 17 February \u2013 The name [[Syonan-to]] is dropped from the [[Old Ford Factory]] exhibition after a controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/syonan-gallery-renamed-yaacob-apologises-for-pain-the-name-cause-7585602|title=Syonan Gallery renamed, Yaacob apologises for 'pain the name caused'|date=2017-02-17|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n* 18 February \u2013 \n**Tuas Viaduct is opened to traffic, making it Singapore's first road-rail viaduct.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdullah |first1=Zhaki |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-tuas-viaduct-to-open-on-feb-18-tuas-west-mrt-extension-to-open-q2-of-2017 |title=New Tuas viaduct to open on Feb 18; Tuas West MRT extension to open in Q2 of 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=7 November 2019 |date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n**Hougang woman Low Soh Kim wins $162,550 in the [[MediaCorp Channel 8]]'s long-running game show ''The [[Sheng Siong]] Show'', surpassing Ang Siang Kiat's winnings of $135,150 as the biggest winner in the show's history <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://superbrands.s3.amazonaws.com/AAA%20MASTER%202%20PAGE%20PDF%20Case%20Studies/Singapore/Singapore%20Edition%208/Singapore%20Edition%208%20ShengSiong.pdf|title=Superbrands}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ch8sg/videos/the-sheng-siong-show/10154775095075345/|title=The Sheng Siong Show returns for a brand new Season tomorrow at 9 PM exclusively on Channel 8! Facebook|website=Facebook}}{{better source|reason=blog|date=January 2019}}</ref> until on 12 January 2019, where Chen Si Jie's winnings of $193,400 surpasses Low's total.<ref>{{cite web|title=Highest Amount $193,400 won at Sheng Siong show!!|url=https://forums.hardwarezone.com.sg/eat-drink-man-woman-16/highest-amount-%24193-400-won-sheng-siong-show-5972445.html|website=forums.hardwarezone.com|date=12 January 2019|accessdate=12 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113003907/https://forums.hardwarezone.com.sg/eat-drink-man-woman-16/highest-amount-%24193-400-won-sheng-siong-show-5972445.html|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sheng Siong Mega Promotion January 2019 English|url=http://www.shengsiong.com.sg/product_images/promotions/pdf/1%20MG18YEEN.pdf|website=www.shengsiong.com.sg|accessdate=19 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119230905/http://www.shengsiong.com.sg/product_images/promotions/pdf/1%20MG18YEEN.pdf|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sheng Siong Mega Promotion January 2019 Chinese|url=http://www.shengsiong.com.sg/product_images/promotions/pdf/1%20MG18YECN.pdf|website=www.shengsiong.com.sg|accessdate=19 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119230959/http://www.shengsiong.com.sg/product_images/promotions/pdf/1%20MG18YECN.pdf|archive-date=19 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 20 February \u2013 \n**A new SMEs Go Digital Programme is announced to enable [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|SME]]s to digitalise with Industry Digital Plans, in addition to new SME Technology Hub to be set up. A new Tech Access Initiative is announced too.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/budget-2017-more-help-for-smes-to-go-digital-with-focus-on-data--7595594 |title=Budget 2017: More help for SMEs to go digital, with focus on data and cybersecurity |date=20 February 2017 |website=Channel NewsAsia |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n**The Government announced a water price hike of 30% in two phases, fully taking effect on 1 July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-budget-2017-water-prices-to-increase-by-30-from-july-1-in-two-phases|title=Singapore Budget 2017: Water prices to increase by 30% from July 1 in two phases|date=2017-02-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n**A [[carbon tax]] is proposed at an initial rate of $10 to $20 per tonne of emissions, which will be implemented by 2019. Diesel taxes are restructured to a $0.10 volume duty per litre to reduce consumption. The Carbon Emissions-based Vehicle Scheme (CEVS) will be replaced with the Vehicular Emissions Scheme (VES), measuring four more pollutants other than carbon dioxide. The Early Turnover Scheme will be extended by two years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lam |first1=Lydia |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/singapore-budget-2017-singapore-to-implement-carbon-tax-from-2019-2-vehicle |title=Singapore Budget 2017: Singapore to implement carbon tax from 2019; diesel taxes restructured |date=20 February 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref> Motorcycles will be taxed with a three-tier Additional Registration Fee.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Koh |first1=Fabian |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapore-budget-2017-motorcycles-to-get-three-tiered-additional-registration |title=Singapore Budget 2017: Motorcycles to get three-tiered Additional Registration Fee |date=20 February 2017 |website=The Straits Times |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 24 February \u2013 Hillion Mall opens its doors to the public.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Boon|first1=Rachael|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/property/new-bukit-panjang-mall-to-open-in-feb|title=New Bukit Panjang mall to open in Feb|date=2017-01-11|website=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n* 27 February \u2013 Junction Tree debuts as the first bilingual preschool TV programme.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/first-bilingual-tv-programme-for-preschoolers-debuts-on-feb-27-7536814 |title=First bilingual TV programme for preschoolers debuts on Feb 27 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=4 January 2017 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n* 28 February \u2013 \n**[[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|MINDEF]] is hit by a [[cyberattack]] which resulted in 850 personnel being affected.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/mindef-internet-system-hacked-personal-data-850-personnel-stolen|title=Mindef hit by targeted cyber attack|date=2017-02-28|website=Todayonline|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n**The Early Childhood Development Centres Act is passed, setting higher and more consistent standards in running [[child care|childcare centre]]s and [[kindergarten]]s. Among them include a common licencing system lasting for three years each, more investigative powers, higher penalties matching the severity of offences and requiring approval by the Early Childhood Development Agency before working at such centres.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goy |first1=Priscilla |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-higher-standards-for-childcare-centres-and-kindergartens-under-new-law |title=Parliament: Higher standards for childcare centres and kindergartens under new law |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 November 2019 |date=28 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 3 March \u2013 [[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)|MINDEF]] announced plans to create a Defence Cyber Organisation 