3}})}}\n|data-sort-value=\"Maguire, Joseph\" |[[File:Richard Grenell official photo.jpg|frameless|125x125px]]<br>[[Richard Grenell]]\n|February 20, 2020\nActing\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"Director of the Office of Management and Budget\" |[[File:US-OfficeOfManagementAndBudget-Seal.svg|75px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Office of Management and Budget|Director of the Office of Management and Budget]]<br>{{small|({{usc|31|502}}, {{Executive Order|11541}},<br/> {{Executive Order|11609}}, {{Executive Order|11717}})}}\n|data-sort-value=\"Vought, Russell\" |[[File:Russell Vought.jpg|100px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Russell Vought]]\n|January 2, 2019\nActing\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"Director of Central Intelligence Agency\" |[[File:Seal of the Central Intelligence Agency.svg|75px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]]<ref name=\"whitehouse.gov\"/><br>{{small|({{UnitedStatesCode|50|3036}})}}\n|data-sort-value=\"Haspel, Gina\" |[[File:Gina Haspel official CIA portrait (cropped).jpg|100px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Gina Haspel]] \n|April 26, 2018{{refn|Haspel served as Acting Director from April 26, 2018 until May 21, 2018.|group=n}}\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency\" |[[File:Environmental Protection Agency logo.svg|75px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]]<br>{{small|({{usc|5|906}}, {{Executive Order|11735}})}}\n|data-sort-value=\"Wheeler, Andrew\" |[[File:Andrew Wheeler official photo.jpg|100px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]\n|July 9, 2018{{refn|Wheeler served as Acting Administrator from July 9, 2018 until February 28, 2019.|group=n}}\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"Administrator of the Small Business Administration\" |[[File:US-SmallBusinessAdmin-Seal.svg|75px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Administrator of the Small Business Administration]]<br>{{small|({{usc|15|633}})}}\n|data-sort-value=\"Carranza, Jovita\" |[[File:Administrator Jovita Carranza portrait (cropped).jpg|100px|link=|alt=]]<br>[[Jovita Carranza]]\n|January 16, 2020<br>\n|}\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==Former executive and Cabinet-level departments==\n* [[United States Department of War|Department of War]] (1789\u20131947), headed by the [[United States Secretary of War|secretary of war]]: renamed [[United States Department of the Army|Department of the Army]] by the [[National Security Act of 1947]].\n* [[United States Department of the Navy|Department of the Navy]] (1798\u20131949), headed by the [[United States Secretary of the Navy|secretary of the Navy]]: became a military department within the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].\n* [[United States Post Office Department|Post Office Department]] (1829\u20131971), headed by the [[United States Postmaster General|postmaster general]]: reorganized as the [[United States Postal Service]], an [[Independent agencies of the United States government|independent agency]].\n* National Military Establishment (1947\u20131949), headed by the [[United States Secretary of Defense|secretary of Defense]]: created by the [[National Security Act of 1947]] and recreated as the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] in 1949.\n* [[United States Department of the Army|Department of the Army]] (1947\u20131949), headed by the [[United States Secretary of the Army|secretary of the Army]]: became a military department within the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].\n* [[United States Department of the Air Force|Department of the Air Force]] (1947\u20131949), headed by the [[United States Secretary of the Air Force|secretary of the Air Force]]: became a military department within the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].\n\n==Renamed heads of the executive departments==\n* [[United States Secretary of Foreign Affairs|Secretary of Foreign Affairs]]: created in July 1781 and renamed Secretary of State in September 1789.<ref>The office of Secretary of Foreign Affairs existed under the [[Articles of Confederation]] from October 20, 1781 to March 3, 1789, the day before the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] came into force.</ref>\n* [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]]: created in 1789 and was renamed as [[United States Secretary of the Army|Secretary of the Army]] by the [[National Security Act of 1947]]. The 1949 Amendments to the National Security Act of 1947 made the secretary of the Army a subordinate to the secretary of defense.\n* [[United States Secretary of Commerce and Labor|Secretary of Commerce and Labor]]: created in 1903 and renamed [[United States Secretary of Commerce|Secretary of Commerce]] in 1913 when its labor functions were transferred to the new [[United States Secretary of Labor|secretary of labor]].\n* Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare: created in 1953 and renamed [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary of Health and Human Services]] in 1979 when its education functions were transferred to the new [[United States Secretary of Education|secretary of education]].\n\n==Other positions no longer of Cabinet rank==\n* [[Counselor to the President]] (1969\u20131993): A title used by high-ranking political advisers to the president of the United States and senior members of the Executive Office of the President since the Nixon administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/washingtonpost/obituary.aspx?n=clayton-yeutter&pid=184350162|title=Clayton Yeutter's Obituary|website=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231194056/https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/washingtonpost/obituary.aspx?n=clayton-yeutter&pid=184350162|archive-date=December 31, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Incumbents with Cabinet rank included [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]], [[Donald Rumsfeld]] and [[Anne Armstrong]].\n* Director of the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (1996\u20132001): Created as an independent agency in 1979, raised to Cabinet rank in 1996,<ref name=rank>{{cite press release|title=President Clinton Raises FEMA Director to Cabinet Status |publisher=Federal Emergency Management Agency |date=February 26, 1996 |url=http://www.fema.gov/home/NWZ96/cabinet.htm |accessdate=May 22, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970116185236/http://www.fema.gov/home/NWZ96/cabinet.htm |archivedate=January 16, 1997 }}</ref> and dropped from Cabinet rank in 2001.<ref name=cqfema>{{Cite web\n |author      = Fowler, Daniel\n |title       = Emergency Managers Make It Official: They Want FEMA Out of DHS\n |publisher   = CQ Politics\n |date        = November 19, 2008\n |url         = http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=hsnews-000002988269&cpage=1\n |accessdate  = March 3, 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20081129170848/http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=hsnews-000002988269&cpage=1\n |archivedate = November 29, 2008\n |quote       = During the Clinton administration, FEMA Administrator James Lee Witt met with the Cabinet. His successor in the Bush administration, Joe M. Allbaugh, did not.\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}(Archived March 3, 2010, by WebCite at</ref>\n* [[Director of Central Intelligence]] (1995\u20132001)<ref>{{Cite book | last = Tenet | first = George | authorlink = George Tenet | title = At the Center of the Storm | publisher = HarperCollins | location = London | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-06-114778-4 | page = [https://archive.org/details/atcenterofstormm00tene/page/136 136] | quote = Under President Clinton, I was a Cabinet member\u2014a legacy of John Deutch's requirement when he took the job as DCI\u2014but my contacts with the president, while always interesting, were sporadic. I could see him as often as I wanted but was not on a regular schedule. Under President Bush, the DCI lost its Cabinet-level status. | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/atcenterofstormm00tene }}</ref><ref name=com>{{cite magazine\n| author = Schoenfeld, Gabriel\n| title = The CIA Follies (Cont'd.)\n| magazine = Commentary\n| date = July\u2013August 2007\n| url = https://www.commentarymagazine.com/viewarticle.cfm/the-cia-follies--cont-d--10897?page=all\n| accessdate =May 22, 2009\n| quote = Though he was to lose the Cabinet rank he had enjoyed under Clinton, he came to enjoy \"extraordinary access\" to the new President, who made it plain that he wanted to be briefed every day.}}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{cite news\n |author       = Sciolino, Elaine\n |title        = C.I.A. Chief Charts His Own Course\n |newspaper    = New York Times\n |date         = September 29, 1996\n |url          = https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/29/us/cia-chief-charts-his-own-course.html\n |accessdate   = May 22, 2009\n |quote        = It is no secret that Mr. Deutch initially turned down the intelligence position, and was rewarded for taking it by getting Cabinet rank.\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130530062105/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/29/us/cia-chief-charts-his-own-course.html\n |archive-date = May 30, 2013\n |url-status     = live\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n* Director of the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]] (1993\u20132009)<ref name=czar>{{Cite web\n |author       = Clinton, Bill\n |title        = Remarks by the President and Lee Brown, Director of Office of National Drug Control Policy\n |publisher    = White House\n |date         = July 1, 1993\n |url          = http://clinton6.nara.gov/1993/07/1993-07-01-presidents-remarks-at-swearing-in-of-lee-brown.html\n |accessdate   = May 22, 2009\n |quote        = We are here today to install a uniquely qualified person to lead our nation's effort in the fight against illegal drugs and what they do to our children, to our streets, and to our communities. And to do it for the first time from a position sitting in the President's Cabinet.\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721050309/http://clinton6.nara.gov/1993/07/1993-07-01-presidents-remarks-at-swearing-in-of-lee-brown.html\n |archive-date = July 21, 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=csm>{{cite news\n| author = Cook, Dave\n| title = New drug czar gets lower rank, promise of higher visibility\n| newspaper = Christian Science Monitor\n| date = March 11, 2009\n| url = http://features.csmonitor.com/politics/2009/03/11/new-drug-czar-gets-lower-rank-promise-of-higher-visibility/\n| accessdate = March 16, 2009\n| quote = For one thing, in the Obama administration the Drug Czar will not have Cabinet status, as the job did during George W. Bush's administration.\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090315040317/http://features.csmonitor.com/politics/2009/03/11/new-drug-czar-gets-lower-rank-promise-of-higher-visibility/\n| archive-date = March 15, 2009\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref>\n* [[Council of Economic Advisers#List of Chairs|Chair of the Council of Economic Advisers]] (2009\u20132017)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/02/08/president-donald-j-trump-announces-his-cabinet|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces His Cabinet|date=2017-02-08|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2017-02-09|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208190158/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/02/08/president-donald-j-trump-announces-his-cabinet|archive-date=February 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/president-trump-announces-his-full-cabinet-roster-044552214.html|title=President Trump announces his full Cabinet roster|access-date=2017-02-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208133808/https://www.yahoo.com/news/president-trump-announces-his-full-cabinet-roster-044552214.html|archive-date=February 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]] (1946\u20131989, 1993\u20132001, 2009\u20132018)\n\n==Proposed Cabinet departments==\n* \n*\"Department of Industry and Commerce\", proposed by Secretary of the Treasury [[William Windom]] in a speech given at a Chamber of Commerce dinner in May 1881.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1881/05/13/98556100.pdf|title=A Department of Commerce|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1881-05-13}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Natural Resources\", proposed by the [[Eisenhower administration]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gFiOK24ZASgC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=Eisenhower%20proposes%20Department%20of%20Natural%20Resources#v=onepage&q=Eisenhower%20proposes%20Department%20of%20Natural%20Resources|title=Improving Management and Organization in Federal Natural Resources and Environmental Functions: Hearing Before the Committee on Governmental Affairs, U. S. Senate|first=DIANE Publishing|last=Company|date=April 1, 1998|publisher=DIANE Publishing|accessdate=February 20, 2017|via=Google Books|quote=Chairman STEVENS. Thank you very much. I think both of you are really pointing in the same direction as this Committee. I do hope we can keep it on a bipartisan basis. Mr. Dean, when I was at the Interior Department, I drafted Eisenhower's Department of Natural Resources proposal, and we have had a series of them that have been presented.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114195305/https://books.google.com/books?id=gFiOK24ZASgC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=Eisenhower%20proposes%20Department%20of%20Natural%20Resources#v=onepage&q=Eisenhower%20proposes%20Department%20of%20Natural%20Resources|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live|isbn=9780788148743}}</ref> President [[Richard Nixon]],<ref name=\"Nixon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=2951|title=116 - Special Message to the Congress on Executive Branch Reorganization|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|quote=The administration is today transmitting to the Congress four bills which, if enacted, would replace seven of the present executive departments and several other agencies with four new departments: the Department of Natural Resources, the Department of Community Development, the Department of Human Resources and the Department of Economic Affairs.|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214101500/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=2951|archive-date=February 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[1976 Republican National Convention|1976 GOP national platform]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=25843|title=Republican Party Platform of 1976|date=August 18, 1976|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|access-date=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094440/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=25843|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and by [[William M. Daley|Bill Daley]] (as a consolidation of the Departments of the Interior and Energy, and the Environmental Protection Agency).<ref>{{Cite web|author=Thrush, Glenn|title=Locked in the Cabinet|work=[[Politico]]|date=November 8, 2013|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2013/11/locked-in-the-cabinet-99374_Page3.html|accessdate=November 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117102623/http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2013/11/locked-in-the-cabinet-99374_Page3.html|archive-date=November 17, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* \"[[Department of Peace]]\", proposed by Senator [[Matthew Neely]] in the 1930s, Congressman [[Dennis Kucinich]], 2020 presidential candidate [[Marianne Williamson]], and other members of the U.S. Congress.<ref name='Schuman'>{{cite book | last = Schuman | first = Frederick L. | title = Why a Department of Peace | publisher = Another Mother for Peace | year = 1969 | location = Beverly Hills | pages = 56 | oclc = 339785 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeacealliance.org/content/view/54/130/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060720174929/http://www.thepeacealliance.org/content/view/54/130/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-07-20|title=History of Legislation to Create a Dept. of Peace}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Social Welfare\", proposed by President [[Franklin Roosevelt]] in January 1937.<ref name=\"Roosevelt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=15342|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|title=10 - Summary of the Report of the Committee on Administrative Management|quote=Overhaul the more than 100 separate departments, boards, commissions, administrations, authorities, corporations, committees, agencies and activities which are now parts of the Executive Branch, and theoretically under the President, and consolidate them within twelve regular departments, which would include the existing ten departments and two new departments, a Department of Social Welfare, and a Department of Public Works. Change the name of the Department of Interior to Department of Conservation.|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213164512/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=15342|archive-date=February 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Public Works\", proposed by President Franklin Roosevelt in January 1937.<ref name=\"Roosevelt\"/>\n* \"Department of Conservation\" (renamed Department of Interior) proposed by President Franklin Roosevelt in January 1937.<ref name=\"Roosevelt\"/>\n* \"Department of Urban Affairs and Housing\", proposed by President [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=8699|title=23 - Special Message to the Congress Transmitting Reorganization Plan 1 of 1962|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214002721/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=8699|archive-date=February 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Business and Labor\", proposed by President [[Lyndon Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=28141|title=121 - Special Message to the Congress: The Quality of American Government|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|quote=In my State of the Union Address, and later in my Budget and Economic Messages to the Congress, I proposed the creation of a new Department of Business and Labor.|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214002341/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=28141|archive-date=February 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Community Development\", proposed by President Richard Nixon; to be chiefly concerned with rural infrastructure development.<ref name=\"Nixon\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3608|title=33 - Special Message to the Congress on Rural Development|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214002722/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=3608|archive-date=February 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Human Resources\" proposed by President Richard Nixon; essentially a revised Department of Health, Education, and Welfare.<ref name=\"Nixon\"/>\n* \"Department of Economic Affairs\" proposed by President Richard Nixon; essentially a consolidation of the Departments of Commerce, Labor, and Agriculture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=2951|title=116 - Special Message to the Congress on Executive Branch Reorganization|work=The University of California, Santa Barbara - The American Presidency Project|quote=The new Department of Economic Affairs would include many of the offices that are now within the Departments of Commerce, Labor and Agriculture. A large part of the Department of Transportation would also be relocated here, including the United States Coast Guard, the Federal Railroad Administration, the St. Lawrence Seaway Development Corporation, the National Transportation Safety Board, the Transportation Systems Center, the Federal Aviation Administration, the Motor Carrier Safety Bureau and most of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. The Small Business Administration, the Science Information Exchange program from the Smithsonian Institution, the National Institute for Occupational Health and Safety from the Department of Health, Education, and Welfare and the Office of Technology Utilization from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration would also be included in the new Department.|access-date=February 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214101500/http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=2951|archive-date=February 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Environmental Protection\", proposed by Senator [[Arlen Specter]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Notebook/Note_02-RMSP3.htm|title=Public Notes on 02-RMSP3|accessdate=February 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613094946/http://www.ontheissues.org/Notebook/Note_02-RMSP3.htm|archive-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Intelligence\", proposed by former [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[John Michael McConnell|Mike McConnell]].<ref>{{Cite web| author = J. Stapelton Roy| title = A Conversation with Michael McConnell| work=[[Council on Foreign Relations]] | date = June 29, 2007| url = http://www.cfr.org/intelligence/conversation-michael-mcconnell-rush-transcript-federal-news-service/p13703| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130117042421/http://www.cfr.org/intelligence/conversation-michael-mcconnell-rush-transcript-federal-news-service/p13703| url-status = dead| archive-date = January 17, 2013| accessdate =January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Global Development\", proposed by the [[Center for Global Development]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cgdev.org/article/time-cabinet-level-us-department-global-development|title=Time for a Cabinet-Level U.S. Department of Global Development|work=The Center for Global Development|access-date=February 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114195305/https://www.cgdev.org/article/time-cabinet-level-us-department-global-development|archive-date=January 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Arts\", proposed by [[Quincy Jones]].<ref>{{Cite web| author = Clarke, Jr., John| title = Quincy Jones Lobbies Obama for Secretary of Culture Post| work = [[Rolling Stone]]| date = January 16, 2009| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/15765/90864| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120908204104/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/15765/90864| url-status = dead| archive-date = September 8, 2012| accessdate = August 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* \"Department of Business\", proposed by President [[Barack Obama]] as a consolidation of the U.S. Department of Commerce's core business and trade functions, the Small Business Administration, the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative, the Export-Import Bank, the Overseas Private Investment Corporation, and the U.S. Trade and Development Agency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/13/president-obama-announces-proposal-reform-reorganize-and-consolidate-gov|title=President Obama Announces proposal to reform, reorganize and consolidate Government|work=Barack Obama White House|access-date=February 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211080315/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/13/president-obama-announces-proposal-reform-reorganize-and-consolidate-gov|archive-date=February 11, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/10/29/obama-suggests-secretary-of-business-in-a-second-term/|work=The Wall Street Journal|title=Obama Suggests 'Secretary of Business' in a 2nd Term - Washington Wire - WSJ|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301053228/http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/10/29/obama-suggests-secretary-of-business-in-a-second-term/|archive-date=March 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"Department of Education and the Workforce\" proposed by President [[Donald Trump]] as a consolidation of the Departments of Education and Labor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2018/06/21/622189097/white-house-proposes-merging-education-and-labor-departments|title=White House Proposes Merging Education And Labor Departments|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621234348/https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2018/06/21/622189097/white-house-proposes-merging-education-and-labor-departments|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*\"Department of Health and Public Welfare\" proposed by President [[Donald Trump]] as a renamed Department of Health and Human Services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Government-Reform-and-Reorg-Plan.pdf|title=Delivering Government Solutions in the 21st Century {{!}} Reform Plan and Reorganization Recommendations|last=|first=|date=2018|website=White House|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412132813/https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Government-Reform-and-Reorg-Plan.pdf|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*\"Department of Economic Development\" proposed by Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] to replace the Commerce Department, subsume other agencies like the Small Business Administration and the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office|Patent and Trademark Office]], and include research and development programs, worker training programs, and export and trade authorities like the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative|Office of the U.S. Trade Representative]] with the a single goal of creating and defending good American jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@teamwarren/a-plan-for-economic-patriotism-13b879f4cfc7|title=A Plan For Economic Patriotism|last=Warren|first=Team|date=2019-06-04|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731023456/https://medium.com/@teamwarren/a-plan-for-economic-patriotism-13b879f4cfc7|archive-date=July 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*\"Department of Technology\" proposed by businessman and 2020 Democratic presidential Candidate [[Andrew Yang]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yang2020.com/policies/regulating-ai-emerging-technologies/|title=Regulate AI and other Emerging Technologies|website=Andrew Yang for President|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820174006/https://www.yang2020.com/policies/regulating-ai-emerging-technologies/|archive-date=August 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*\"Department of Children and Youth\", proposed by Marianne Williamson.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Black Cabinet]]\n* [[Brain trust]]\n* [[Cabinet of Donald Trump]]\n* [[Cabinet of the Confederate States of America]]\n* [[Kitchen Cabinet]]\n* [[List of African-American United States Cabinet Secretaries]]\n* [[List of female United States Cabinet Secretaries]]\n* [[List of foreign-born United States Cabinet Secretaries]]\n* [[List of living former members of the United States Cabinet]]\n* [[List of people who have held multiple United States Cabinet-level positions]]\n* [[List of United States Cabinet members who have served more than eight years]]\n* [[List of United States political appointments that crossed party lines]]\n* [[St. Wapniacl]] (historical mnemonic acronym)\n* [[Unsuccessful nominations to the Cabinet of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bennett, Anthony. ''The American President's Cabinet''. Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire: Macmillan, 1996. {{ISBN|0-333-60691-4}}. A study of the U.S. Cabinet from Kennedy to Clinton.\n* Grossman, Mark. ''Encyclopedia of the United States Cabinet'' (Santa Barbara, California: ABC-CLIO; three volumes, 2000; reprint, New York: Greyhouse Publishing; two volumes, 2010). A history of the United States and Confederate States Cabinets, their secretaries, and their departments.\n* Rudalevige, Andrew. \"The President and the Cabinet\", in Michael Nelson, ed., ''The Presidency and the Political System'', 8th ed. (Washington, D.C.: CQ Press, 2006).\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|United States Cabinet}}\n* [https://www.whitehouse.gov/administration/cabinet Official site of the President's Cabinet]\n* [https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/resources/pdf/StateUnionCabinet.pdf U.S. Senate's list of Cabinet members who did not attend the State of the Union Address (since 1984)]\n\n{{Current U.S. Cabinet}}\n{{USCabinet}}\n{{US Order of Precedence}}\n{{United States topics}}\n{{North America topic|Cabinet of |title=National Cabinets of North America}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cabinet Of The United States}}\n[[Category:Cabinet of the United States| ]]\n[[Category:National cabinets|United States]]\n", "name_user": "Thevioletflower", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix of grammer.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cabinet_of_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "5th (Cyclist) Battalion, East Yorkshire Regiment", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 2nd Volunteer Bn, East Yorkshire Regiment<br>5th (Cyclist) Bn, East Yorkshire Regiment\n|image=Badge,_regimental_(AM_790881-1).jpg\n|image_size=350px\n|caption=Cap badge of the East Yorkshire Regiment, granted to the battalion in 1885\n|dates=1860\u20131920\n|country={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[File:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[Territorial Force]]\n|type=Infantry<br>Cycle troops\n|role=Mobile coastal defence \n|size=Battalion \n|command_structure=[[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern Command]]\n|current_commander=\n|garrison= [[Beverley]] (2nd VB)<br>[[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] (5th Bn)\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|nickname= \n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|notable_commanders= Lt-Col [[Sir Robert Aske, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Aske]]\n|anniversaries=\n}}\nThe '''5th (Cyclist) Battalion, East Yorkshire Regiment''' was a mobile coast defence unit of Britain's [[Territorial Force]]. It was formed in 1908 from a nucleus provided by a [[Volunteer Force|Volunteer]] battalion first raised in 1859. It carried out its defence duties along the East Coast throughout [[World War I]] and after the war it was incorporated into a unit of the new [[Royal Corps of Signals]].\n\n==Volunteer Force==\nThe enthusiasm for the [[Volunteer movement]] following an invasion scare in 1859 saw the creation of many Rifle Volunteer Corps (RVCs) composed of part-time soldiers eager to supplement the Regular [[British Army]] in time of need.<ref>Beckett.</ref><ref>Spiers, pp. 163\u20138.</ref> A public meeting to form an RVC in [[Kingston upon Hull]] (Hull) in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] was held in February 1859, but the proposal was defeated by an active minority on political grounds. However, another meeting held on 21 May resolved to raise the '''East Yorkshire Rifle Volunteers''', and 10 independent company-sized RVCs were quickly formed, their officers receiving their commissions the following year. In 1860 these were formed into two battalions: the [[Hull Rifles|1st (Consolidated) Battalion]], comprising all the RVCs in Hull, and the '''2nd (Administrative) Battalion East York Rifle Volunteers''' incorporating those outside the town:<ref name = List>''Army List'', various dates.</ref><ref>Beckett, Appendix VII.</ref><ref name = Norfolk>Norfolk, pp. 35\u201340, 56.</ref><ref name = Westlake>Westlake, pp. 253\u20134.</ref>\n* 3rd ([[Howdenshire]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 28 March 1860 \u2013 replacing an earlier 3rd (Hull) RVC absorbed into 1st Bn\n* 5th ([[Bridlington]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 19 January 1860\n* 6th ([[Beverley]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 28 February 1860\n* 8th ([[Driffield]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 11 May 1860\n* 9th ([[Market Weighton]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC \u2013 formed as a sub-division 12 May 1860, increased into a full company in 1865 when it replaced a short-lived 9th (Hull) RVC\n* 10th ([[Hedon]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 8 November 1860 \u2013 disbanded 1876\n* 11th ([[Pocklington]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC \u2013 formed 8 August 1868 under the command of [[Josslyn Pennington, 5th Baron Muncaster|Lord Muncaster]], formerly of the [[Rifle Brigade]]\n\nThe first commanding officer (CO) of the 2nd (Admin) Battalion was [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]] (later [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]]) P. Saltmarshe, formerly of the [[8th Hussars]], with his headquarters (HQ) at Beverley. After the consolidated battalion became the 1st Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC the administrative battalion took the number 1 (though there were no others in the East Riding). It consolidated as the 2nd Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC in 1880 when the constituent RVCs became A to F Companies. The two corps became the [[Hull Rifles|1st]] and 2nd Volunteer Battalions (VBs) of the [[East Yorkshire Regiment]] in 1883.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref name = Westlake/>\n\nFrom the 1870s to the 1890s the two VBs organised their own annual training camps, usually at Bridlington.<ref name = Norfolk/> Higher formations for the Volunteers were lacking, but from 1875 various mobilisation schemes for the Regulars and Militia began to be circulated, and by 1880 a number of Local Brigades had begun to appear in the ''Army List''. B Company of the 2nd VB was included in Local Brigade No 25 at Bridlington, along with two batteries of volunteer artillery.<ref name = List/> Following the [[Stanhope Memorandum]] of December 1888 a comprehensive mobilisation scheme was introduced for Volunteer units, which would assemble in their own brigades at key points in case of war. In peacetime these brigades provided a structure for collective training.<ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 185\u20136.</ref><ref>Dunlop, pp. 60\u20131.</ref> The two East Yorkshire VBs did not at first form part of the East Yorkshire Brigade, whose designated place of assembly was [[Doncaster]], but were attached to it by the end of the 1890s when its headquarters was at [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]. By 1902 they were brigaded with the VBs of the [[Green Howards]] as the Yorkshire Brigade at [[Richmond, North Yorkshire]], and later formed the Humber Brigade based at Beverley, together with battalions from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] and [[Lincolnshire]] across the [[Humber]].<ref name = List/>\n\nThe late Victorian era saw a craze for cycling and the Volunteer Force took a leading role in developing the new [[Safety bicycle]] for military use. In 1893 the East Yorkshire VBs raised a cyclist section that proved so popular that it was enlarged into a full company.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 200\u20131.</ref><ref>Anon, ''London Cyclist Battalion''.</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\nAfter [[Black Week]] in December 1899, the Volunteers were invited to send active service units to assist the Regulars in the [[Second Boer War]]. The [[War Office]] decided that one company 116 strong could be recruited from the volunteer battalions of any infantry regiment that had a regular battalion serving in South Africa. The two VBs accordingly raised a service company under Major Mortimer of Driffield to serve with the 2nd Battalion.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref>Beckett, p. 213.</ref> This earned the VBs the [[Battle Honour]] 'South Africa 1900\u201301'.<ref name = List/>\n\n==Territorial Force==\n[[File:The_British_Army_on_the_Home_Front,_1914-1918_Q30445.jpg|thumb|right|British Army cyclist in marching order, 1914\u201318.]]\nWhen the Volunteers were subsumed into the new [[Territorial Force]] (TF) under the [[Haldane Reforms]] of 1908,<ref>Beckett, pp. 247\u201353.</ref><ref>Dunlop, Chapter 14.</ref><ref>Spiers, Chapter 10.</ref> the 2nd VB including the cyclist company formed the nucleus of the '''5th (Cyclist) Battalion, East Yorkshire Regiment''', although the new unit's HQ and half the companies were based in Hull:<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts>{{Cite web |url=http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-5cycl.htm |title=5th (Cyclist) Bn East Yorkshires at Regiments.org. |access-date=2005-12-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051227060846/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-5cycl.htm |archive-date=2005-12-27 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.wartimememoriesproject.com/greatwar/allied/battalion.php?pid=566 5th (Cyclist) Bn East Yorkshires at Wartime Memories Project.]</ref>{{efn|The 5th Bn was considered a new unit and did not receive the 'South Africa 1900\u201301' Battle Honour earned by the 2nd VB.<ref name = List/>}}\n* HQ at Park Street, Hull (formerly the Artillery Barracks occupied by the [[2nd East Riding Artillery Volunteers]]<ref>[https://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHull.htm Hull at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>)\n* A, B, C, and D Companies at Hull\n* E Company at Shire Hall, Market Place, [[Howden]]<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHowden.htm Howden at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>\n* F Company at Greyburn Lane, Beverley;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownBeverley.htm Beverley at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Drill Hall, Southgate, [[Hessle]];<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHessle.htm Hessle at  Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Southgate, Market Weighton;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownMarketWeighton.htm Market Weighton at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> and Barmby Road, Pocklington<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownPocklington.htm Pocklington at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>\n* G Company at Armoury, Quay Road, Bridlington;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownBridlington.htm Bridlington at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Drill Hall, Middle Street South, Driffield;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownDriffield.htm Driffield at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> [[Hunmanby]]; and [[Filey]]\n* H Company at Hedon and [[Withernsea]]\n\nThe cyclist battalions were not included in the TF's main divisional structure but were instead given the role of using their mobility to defend vulnerable sectors of the coastline and maintain communications between the static defence units.<ref>Anon, ''London Cyclist Battalion'', p. 106.</ref> The 5th Bn East Yorkshires fulfilled this role in [[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern Command]].<ref name = List/>\n\n==World War I==\n[[File:Robert Aske.jpg|thumb|right|Local politician and commanding officer of the 1/5th (Cyclist) Bn Sir Robert Aske.]]\nOn the declaration of war in August 1914 the battalion mobilised at Park Street under the command of Lt-Col [[Sir Robert Aske, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Aske]], a local lawyer and politician who was first commissioned into the 1st VB on 9 February 1898 and became Commanding Officer of the 5th Bn on 20 August 1910. It moved out to its designated war station at [[Louth, Lincolnshire]] to begin patrolling the coastline from [[Tetney]] to [[Skegness]].<ref name = List/><ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/28408/page/6041 ''London Gazette'', 19 August 1910.]</ref><ref>Wyrall, pp. 1, 20\u20131.</ref><ref name = Trail>[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/regiments-and-corps/the-british-infantry-regiments-of-1914-1918/east-yorkshire-regiment/ East Yorkshires at Long, Long Trail.]</ref>\n\nShortly after the outbreak of war, TF units were invited to volunteer for Overseas Service. On 15 August 1914, the War Office issued instructions to separate those men who had signed up for Home Service only, and form these into reserve units. On 31 August, the formation of a reserve or 2nd Line unit was authorised for each 1st Line unit where 60 per cent or more of the men had volunteered for Overseas Service. The titles of these 2nd Line units would be the same as the original, but distinguished by a '2/' prefix, and would be filled up with the recruits who were flooding in for both the TF and '[[Kitchener's Army]]'.<ref>Becke, Pt 2b, p. 6.</ref><ref>BIlton, ''Hull in the Great War'', p. 73.</ref>\n\nAt first, competition was keen to join the Cyclist Battalion, which was seen as rather glamorous, with distinctive knee breeches and black bugle buttons.<ref>Bilton, ''Hull Pals'', pp. 24\u20135.</ref> However, the battalion lost out to the other units being formed in Hull, particularly the '[[Hull Pals]]', a full brigade of whom were raised for Kitchener's Army by [[Charles Wilson, 2nd Baron Nunburnholme|Lord Nunburnholme]].<ref>Bilton, ''Hull Pals''.</ref> In March 1915 the cycle unit was designated 1/5th Battalion, in expectation of a 2nd Line unit, but it appears that the 2/5th Battalion was never formed \u2013 in November 1914 the battalion still required 900 recruits.<ref name = Regts/><ref>Bilton, ''Hull in the Great War'', p. 91.</ref> Those men who had enlisted for home service only were formed into 2nd Provisional Cyclist Company in July 1915. The latter served in the Humber Defences until it was disbanded on 13 April 1916 after the [[Military Service Act 1916]] swept away the Home/Foreign service distinction.<ref name = Regts/>\n\nThe 1/5th (Cyclist) Battalion patrolled the [[Lincolnshire]] coast through the winter of 1914\u201315, day and night, in all weathers. In May 1915 it moved to [[Withernsea]] on the [[Yorkshire Coast]], and subsequently to [[Roos]], with its companies distributed between [[Spurn Head]] and [[Bridlington]]. In January 1916 it adopted the modern four-company organisation in place of eight companies, and was allotted to the northern section of the Humber Defences.<ref>Wyrall, p. 401.</ref>{{efn|The battalion may have later moved to [[Newbiggin-by-the-Sea]] and become part of the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] Garrison.<ref name = Trail/>}} Sir Robert Aske retired and was transferred to the TF Reserve on 24 December 1917;<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/30493/supplement/1208 ''London Gazette'', 25 January 1918.]</ref> he was later awarded the [[Territorial Decoration]].<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/30696/supplement/6046 ''London Gazette'', 22 May 1918.]</ref>\n\nThe battalion never saw active service, though a number of officers and men served with other battalions of the East Yorkshires.<ref>Bilton, Hull Pals, Appendices 9\u201313.</ref>\n\n==Disbandment==\nAfter the war the battalion was reformed on 7 February 1920, but shortly afterwards cyclist battalions were abolished and it was amalgamated into [[50 (Northumbrian) Signal Regiment|50th (Northumbrian) Divisional Signals]] in the new [[Royal Corps of Signals]]. The merged unit moved its HQ to 4 West Parade in Hull, but later it went to [[Darlington]].<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts/><ref>Lord & Watson, pp. 161\u20132.</ref><ref>Nalder, p. 161.</ref><ref>Wyrall, p. 402.</ref>{{efn|A new 5th Bn East Yorkshires was formed in 1939 as a wartime duplicate of the 4th Bn.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051227043223/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-e4.htm 4th Bn East Yorkshires at Regiments.org.]</ref>}}\n\n==Uniforms and insignia==\nThe first meeting of the East Yorkshire Rifle Volunteers in Hull in 1859 decided that the uniform would be green. However, the [[Vice Lord Lieutenant]] objected, asserting that the [[Battle of Inkerman]] had shown that the grey worn by Russian troops was less visible at shorter distances than [[Rifle green]]. Reluctantly the units agreed to a uniform of 'Volunteer' grey with black braid and red [[Facing colour|facings]] and trouser stripe. The headgear was a grey [[Shako]] with black leather peak and top. The belts and pouch were black leather. In 1880 a scarlet tunic was adopted with white facings, blue trousers with red stripe, and white belts. The headgear was the [[Home Service helmet]] for officers, a [[Glengarry]] cap for other ranks. In 1885 the VBs were granted the right to wear the cap badge of the East Yorkshire Regiment. In 1903 the Cyclist Company adopted a [[Khaki]] service dress with a [[Slouch hat]]. The rest of the battalion adopted khaki in 1906.<ref name = Norfolk/>\n\n==Honorary Colonels==\nThe following served as [[Colonel (United Kingdom)#Ceremonial usage|Honorary Colonel]] of the unit and its predecessor:<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts/>\n*[[William Denison, 1st Earl of Londesborough|William Henry Forester Denison, 1st Earl of Londesborough]] (1834\u20131900) appointed to 2nd VB 9 September 1893 \n* [[Earl of Londesborough|William Francis Henry Denison, 2nd Earl of Londesborough]] (1864\u20131917) appointed to 2nd VB 4 August 1900; to 5th Bn 1 October 1909\n* Capt [[Charles Wilson, 2nd Baron Nunburnholme]], [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], appointed 21 November 1917\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n* Anon, ''The London Cyclist Battalion'', London: 25th London Cyclist Old Comrade's Association/Forster Groom, 1932.\n* Ian F.W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A Study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0 85936 271 X}}.\n* David Bilton, ''Hull in the Great War 1914\u20131919'', Barnsley: Pen & Sword, 2015, {{ISBN|978-1-47382-314-3}}.\n* David Bilton, ''Hull Pals, 10th, 11th 12th and 13th Battalions East Yorkshire Regiment \u2013 A History of 92 Infantry Brigade, 31st Division'', Barnsley: Pen & Sword, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1-78346-185-1}}.\n* Col John K. Dunlop, ''The Development of the British Army 1899\u20131914'', London: Methuen, 1938.\n* Cliff Lord & Graham Watson, ''Royal Corps of Signals: Unit Histories of the Corps (1920\u20132001) and its Antecedents'', Solihull: Helion, 2003, {{ISBN|1-874622-92-2}}.\n* Maj-Gen R.F.H. Nalder, ''The Royal Corps of Signals: A History of its Antecedents and Developments (Circa 1800\u20131955)'', London: Royal Signals Institution, 1958.\n* R.W.S. Norfolk, ''Militia, Yeomanry and Volunteer Forces of the East Riding 1689\u20131908'', York: East Yorkshire Local History Society, 1965.\n* Edward M. Spiers, ''The Army and Society 1815\u20131914'', London: Longmans, 1980, {{ISBN|0-582-48565-7}}.\n* Ray Westlake, ''Tracing the Rifle Volunteers'', Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-84884-211-3}}.\n* Everard Wyrall, ''The East Yorkshire Regiment in the Great War 1914\u20131918'', London: Harrison, 1928/Uckfield,Naval & Military, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1-84342-211-2}}\n\n==External sources==\n* [http://www.drillhalls.org/index.htm The Drill Hall Project]\n* [http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk The Long, Long Trail]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051228103659/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/index.htm Land Forces of Britain, the Empire and Commonwealth \u2013 Regiments.org (archive site)]\n* [https://www.wartimememoriesproject.com Wartime Memories Project]\n\n[[Category:East Yorkshire Regiment]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1908]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1920]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 2nd Volunteer Bn, East Yorkshire Regiment<br>5th (Cyclist) Bn, East Yorkshire Regiment\n|image=Badge,_regimental_(AM_790881-1).jpg\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Cap badge of the East Yorkshire Regiment, granted to the battalion in 1885\n|dates=1860\u20131920\n|country={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch=[[File:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[Territorial Force]]\n|type=Infantry<br>Cycle troops\n|role=Mobile coastal defence \n|size=Battalion \n|command_structure=[[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern Command]]\n|current_commander=\n|garrison= [[Beverley]] (2nd VB)<br>[[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] (5th Bn)\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|colonel_of_the_regiment=\n|nickname= \n|patron=\n|motto=\n|colors=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|battles=\n|notable_commanders= Lt-Col [[Sir Robert Aske, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Aske]]\n|anniversaries=\n}}\nThe '''5th (Cyclist) Battalion, East Yorkshire Regiment''' was a mobile coast defence unit of Britain's [[Territorial Force]]. It was formed in 1908 from a nucleus provided by a [[Volunteer Force|Volunteer]] battalion first raised in 1859. It carried out its defence duties along the East Coast throughout [[World War I]] and after the war it was incorporated into a unit of the new [[Royal Corps of Signals]].\n\n==Volunteer Force==\nThe enthusiasm for the [[Volunteer movement]] following an invasion scare in 1859 saw the creation of many Rifle Volunteer Corps (RVCs) composed of part-time soldiers eager to supplement the Regular [[British Army]] in time of need.<ref>Beckett.</ref><ref>Spiers, pp. 163\u20138.</ref> A public meeting to form an RVC in [[Kingston upon Hull]] (Hull) in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] was held in February 1859, but the proposal was defeated by an active minority on political grounds. However, another meeting held on 21 May resolved to raise the '''East Yorkshire Rifle Volunteers''', and 10 independent company-sized RVCs were quickly formed, their officers receiving their commissions the following year. In 1860 these were formed into two battalions: the [[Hull Rifles|1st (Consolidated) Battalion]], comprising all the RVCs in Hull, and the '''2nd (Administrative) Battalion East York Rifle Volunteers''' incorporating those outside the town:<ref name = List>''Army List'', various dates.</ref><ref>Beckett, Appendix VII.</ref><ref name = Norfolk>Norfolk, pp. 35\u201340, 56.</ref><ref name = Westlake>Westlake, pp. 253\u20134.</ref>\n* 3rd ([[Howdenshire]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 28 March 1860 \u2013 replacing an earlier 3rd (Hull) RVC absorbed into 1st Bn\n* 5th ([[Bridlington]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 19 January 1860\n* 6th ([[Beverley]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 28 February 1860\n* 8th ([[Driffield]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 11 May 1860\n* 9th ([[Market Weighton]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC \u2013 formed as a sub-division 12 May 1860, increased into a full company in 1865 when it replaced a short-lived 9th (Hull) RVC\n* 10th ([[Hedon]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC, 8 November 1860 \u2013 disbanded 1876\n* 11th ([[Pocklington]]) Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC \u2013 formed 8 August 1868 under the command of [[Josslyn Pennington, 5th Baron Muncaster|Lord Muncaster]], formerly of the [[Rifle Brigade]]\n\nThe first commanding officer (CO) of the 2nd (Admin) Battalion was [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]] (later [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]]) P. Saltmarshe, formerly of the [[8th Hussars]], with his headquarters (HQ) at Beverley. After the consolidated battalion became the 1st Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC the administrative battalion took the number 1 (though there were no others in the East Riding). It consolidated as the 2nd Yorkshire (East Riding) RVC in 1880 when the constituent RVCs became A to F Companies. The two corps became the [[Hull Rifles|1st]] and 2nd Volunteer Battalions (VBs) of the [[East Yorkshire Regiment]] in 1883.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref name = Westlake/>\n\nFrom the 1870s to the 1890s the two VBs organised their own annual training camps, usually at Bridlington.<ref name = Norfolk/> Higher formations for the Volunteers were lacking, but from 1875 various mobilisation schemes for the Regulars and Militia began to be circulated, and by 1880 a number of Local Brigades had begun to appear in the ''Army List''. B Company of the 2nd VB was included in Local Brigade No 25 at Bridlington, along with two batteries of volunteer artillery.<ref name = List/> Following the [[Stanhope Memorandum]] of December 1888 a comprehensive mobilisation scheme was introduced for Volunteer units, which would assemble in their own brigades at key points in case of war. In peacetime these brigades provided a structure for collective training.<ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 185\u20136.</ref><ref>Dunlop, pp. 60\u20131.</ref> The two East Yorkshire VBs did not at first form part of the East Yorkshire Brigade, whose designated place of assembly was [[Doncaster]], but were attached to it by the end of the 1890s when its headquarters was at [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]. By 1902 they were brigaded with the VBs of the [[Green Howards]] as the Yorkshire Brigade at [[Richmond, North Yorkshire]], and later formed the Humber Brigade based at Beverley, together with battalions from the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] and [[Lincolnshire]] across the [[Humber]].<ref name = List/>\n\nThe late Victorian era saw a craze for cycling and the Volunteer Force took a leading role in developing the new [[Safety bicycle]] for military use. In 1893 the East Yorkshire VBs raised a cyclist section that proved so popular that it was enlarged into a full company.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 200\u20131.</ref><ref>Anon, ''London Cyclist Battalion''.</ref>\n\n==South Africa==\nAfter [[Black Week]] in December 1899, the Volunteers were invited to send active service units to assist the Regulars in the [[Second Boer War]]. The [[War Office]] decided that one company 116 strong could be recruited from the volunteer battalions of any infantry regiment that had a regular battalion serving in South Africa. The two VBs accordingly raised a service company under Major Mortimer of Driffield to serve with the 2nd Battalion.<ref name = Norfolk/><ref>Beckett, p. 213.</ref> This earned the VBs the [[Battle Honour]] 'South Africa 1900\u201301'.<ref name = List/>\n\n==Territorial Force==\n[[File:The_British_Army_on_the_Home_Front,_1914-1918_Q30445.jpg|thumb|right|British Army cyclist in marching order, 1914\u201318.]]\nWhen the Volunteers were subsumed into the new [[Territorial Force]] (TF) under the [[Haldane Reforms]] of 1908,<ref>Beckett, pp. 247\u201353.</ref><ref>Dunlop, Chapter 14.</ref><ref>Spiers, Chapter 10.</ref> the 2nd VB including the cyclist company formed the nucleus of the '''5th (Cyclist) Battalion, East Yorkshire Regiment''', although the new unit's HQ and half the companies were based in Hull:<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts>{{Cite web |url=http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-5cycl.htm |title=5th (Cyclist) Bn East Yorkshires at Regiments.org. |access-date=2005-12-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051227060846/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-5cycl.htm |archive-date=2005-12-27 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.wartimememoriesproject.com/greatwar/allied/battalion.php?pid=566 5th (Cyclist) Bn East Yorkshires at Wartime Memories Project.]</ref>{{efn|The 5th Bn was considered a new unit and did not receive the 'South Africa 1900\u201301' Battle Honour earned by the 2nd VB.<ref name = List/>}}\n* HQ at Park Street, Hull (formerly the Artillery Barracks occupied by the [[2nd East Riding Artillery Volunteers]]<ref>[https://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHull.htm Hull at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>)\n* A, B, C, and D Companies at Hull\n* E Company at Shire Hall, Market Place, [[Howden]]<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHowden.htm Howden at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>\n* F Company at Greyburn Lane, Beverley;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownBeverley.htm Beverley at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Drill Hall, Southgate, [[Hessle]];<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownHessle.htm Hessle at  Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Southgate, Market Weighton;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownMarketWeighton.htm Market Weighton at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> and Barmby Road, Pocklington<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownPocklington.htm Pocklington at Drill Hall Project.]</ref>\n* G Company at Armoury, Quay Road, Bridlington;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownBridlington.htm Bridlington at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> Drill Hall, Middle Street South, Driffield;<ref>[http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Yorkshire/TownDriffield.htm Driffield at Drill Hall Project.]</ref> [[Hunmanby]]; and [[Filey]]\n* H Company at Hedon and [[Withernsea]]\n\nThe cyclist battalions were not included in the TF's main divisional structure but were instead given the role of using their mobility to defend vulnerable sectors of the coastline and maintain communications between the static defence units.<ref>Anon, ''London Cyclist Battalion'', p. 106.</ref> The 5th Bn East Yorkshires fulfilled this role in [[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern Command]].<ref name = List/>\n\n==World War I==\n[[File:Robert Aske.jpg|thumb|right|Local politician and commanding officer of the 1/5th (Cyclist) Bn Sir Robert Aske.]]\nOn the declaration of war in August 1914 the battalion mobilised at Park Street under the command of Lt-Col [[Sir Robert Aske, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Aske]], a local lawyer and politician who was first commissioned into the 1st VB on 9 February 1898 and became Commanding Officer of the 5th Bn on 20 August 1910. It moved out to its designated war station at [[Louth, Lincolnshire]] to begin patrolling the coastline from [[Tetney]] to [[Skegness]].<ref name = List/><ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/28408/page/6041 ''London Gazette'', 19 August 1910.]</ref><ref>Wyrall, pp. 1, 20\u20131.</ref><ref name = Trail>[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/regiments-and-corps/the-british-infantry-regiments-of-1914-1918/east-yorkshire-regiment/ East Yorkshires at Long, Long Trail.]</ref>\n\nShortly after the outbreak of war, TF units were invited to volunteer for Overseas Service. On 15 August 1914, the War Office issued instructions to separate those men who had signed up for Home Service only, and form these into reserve units. On 31 August, the formation of a reserve or 2nd Line unit was authorised for each 1st Line unit where 60 per cent or more of the men had volunteered for Overseas Service. The titles of these 2nd Line units would be the same as the original, but distinguished by a '2/' prefix, and would be filled up with the recruits who were flooding in for both the TF and '[[Kitchener's Army]]'.<ref>Becke, Pt 2b, p. 6.</ref><ref>BIlton, ''Hull in the Great War'', p. 73.</ref>\n\nAt first, competition was keen to join the Cyclist Battalion, which was seen as rather glamorous, with distinctive knee breeches and black bugle buttons.<ref>Bilton, ''Hull Pals'', pp. 24\u20135.</ref> However, the battalion lost out to the other units being formed in Hull, particularly the '[[Hull Pals]]', a full brigade of whom were raised for Kitchener's Army by [[Charles Wilson, 2nd Baron Nunburnholme|Lord Nunburnholme]].<ref>Bilton, ''Hull Pals''.</ref> In March 1915 the cycle unit was designated 1/5th Battalion, in expectation of a 2nd Line unit, but it appears that the 2/5th Battalion was never formed \u2013 in November 1914 the battalion still required 900 recruits.<ref name = Regts/><ref>Bilton, ''Hull in the Great War'', p. 91.</ref> Those men who had enlisted for home service only were formed into 2nd Provisional Cyclist Company in July 1915. The latter served in the Humber Defences until it was disbanded on 13 April 1916 after the [[Military Service Act 1916]] swept away the Home/Foreign service distinction.<ref name = Regts/>\n\nThe 1/5th (Cyclist) Battalion patrolled the [[Lincolnshire]] coast through the winter of 1914\u201315, day and night, in all weathers. In May 1915 it moved to [[Withernsea]] on the [[Yorkshire Coast]], and subsequently to [[Roos]], with its companies distributed between [[Spurn Head]] and [[Bridlington]]. In January 1916 it adopted the modern four-company organisation in place of eight companies, and was allotted to the northern section of the Humber Defences.<ref>Wyrall, p. 401.</ref>{{efn|The battalion may have later moved to [[Newbiggin-by-the-Sea]] and become part of the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] Garrison.<ref name = Trail/>}} Sir Robert Aske retired and was transferred to the TF Reserve on 24 December 1917;<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/30493/supplement/1208 ''London Gazette'', 25 January 1918.]</ref> he was later awarded the [[Territorial Decoration]].<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/30696/supplement/6046 ''London Gazette'', 22 May 1918.]</ref>\n\nThe battalion never saw active service, though a number of officers and men served with other battalions of the East Yorkshires.<ref>Bilton, Hull Pals, Appendices 9\u201313.</ref>\n\n==Disbandment==\nAfter the war the battalion was reformed on 7 February 1920, but shortly afterwards cyclist battalions were abolished and it was amalgamated into [[50 (Northumbrian) Signal Regiment|50th (Northumbrian) Divisional Signals]] in the new [[Royal Corps of Signals]]. The merged unit moved its HQ to 4 West Parade in Hull, but later it went to [[Darlington]].<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts/><ref>Lord & Watson, pp. 161\u20132.</ref><ref>Nalder, p. 161.</ref><ref>Wyrall, p. 402.</ref>{{efn|A new 5th Bn East Yorkshires was formed in 1939 as a wartime duplicate of the 4th Bn.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051227043223/http://regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/ye-e4.htm 4th Bn East Yorkshires at Regiments.org.]</ref>}}\n\n==Uniforms and insignia==\nThe first meeting of the East Yorkshire Rifle Volunteers in Hull in 1859 decided that the uniform would be green. However, the [[Vice Lord Lieutenant]] objected, asserting that the [[Battle of Inkerman]] had shown that the grey worn by Russian troops was less visible at shorter distances than [[Rifle green]]. Reluctantly the units agreed to a uniform of 'Volunteer' grey with black braid and red [[Facing colour|facings]] and trouser stripe. The headgear was a grey [[Shako]] with black leather peak and top. The belts and pouch were black leather. In 1880 a scarlet tunic was adopted with white facings, blue trousers with red stripe, and white belts. The headgear was the [[Home Service helmet]] for officers, a [[Glengarry]] cap for other ranks. In 1885 the VBs were granted the right to wear the cap badge of the East Yorkshire Regiment. In 1903 the Cyclist Company adopted a [[Khaki]] service dress with a [[Slouch hat]]. The rest of the battalion adopted khaki in 1906.<ref name = Norfolk/>\n\n==Honorary Colonels==\nThe following served as [[Colonel (United Kingdom)#Ceremonial usage|Honorary Colonel]] of the unit and its predecessor:<ref name = List/><ref name = Regts/>\n*[[William Denison, 1st Earl of Londesborough|William Henry Forester Denison, 1st Earl of Londesborough]] (1834\u20131900) appointed to 2nd VB 9 September 1893 \n* [[Earl of Londesborough|William Francis Henry Denison, 2nd Earl of Londesborough]] (1864\u20131917) appointed to 2nd VB 4 August 1900; to 5th Bn 1 October 1909\n* Capt [[Charles Wilson, 2nd Baron Nunburnholme]], [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], appointed 21 November 1917\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n* Anon, ''The London Cyclist Battalion'', London: 25th London Cyclist Old Comrade's Association/Forster Groom, 1932.\n* Ian F.W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A Study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0 85936 271 X}}.\n* David Bilton, ''Hull in the Great War 1914\u20131919'', Barnsley: Pen & Sword, 2015, {{ISBN|978-1-47382-314-3}}.\n* David Bilton, ''Hull Pals, 10th, 11th 12th and 13th Battalions East Yorkshire Regiment \u2013 A History of 92 Infantry Brigade, 31st Division'', Barnsley: Pen & Sword, 2014, {{ISBN|978-1-78346-185-1}}.\n* Col John K. Dunlop, ''The Development of the British Army 1899\u20131914'', London: Methuen, 1938.\n* Cliff Lord & Graham Watson, ''Royal Corps of Signals: Unit Histories of the Corps (1920\u20132001) and its Antecedents'', Solihull: Helion, 2003, {{ISBN|1-874622-92-2}}.\n* Maj-Gen R.F.H. Nalder, ''The Royal Corps of Signals: A History of its Antecedents and Developments (Circa 1800\u20131955)'', London: Royal Signals Institution, 1958.\n* R.W.S. Norfolk, ''Militia, Yeomanry and Volunteer Forces of the East Riding 1689\u20131908'', York: East Yorkshire Local History Society, 1965.\n* Edward M. Spiers, ''The Army and Society 1815\u20131914'', London: Longmans, 1980, {{ISBN|0-582-48565-7}}.\n* Ray Westlake, ''Tracing the Rifle Volunteers'', Barnsley: Pen and Sword, 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-84884-211-3}}.\n* Everard Wyrall, ''The East Yorkshire Regiment in the Great War 1914\u20131918'', London: Harrison, 1928/Uckfield,Naval & Military, 2002, {{ISBN|978-1-84342-211-2}}\n\n==External sources==\n* [http://www.drillhalls.org/index.htm The Drill Hall Project]\n* [http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk The Long, Long Trail]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051228103659/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/index.htm Land Forces of Britain, the Empire and Commonwealth \u2013 Regiments.org (archive site)]\n* [https://www.wartimememoriesproject.com Wartime Memories Project]\n\n[[Category:East Yorkshire Regiment]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1908]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1920]]\n", "name_user": "Rickfive", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/5th_(Cyclist)_Battalion,_East_Yorkshire_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "Don Blankenship", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Don Blankenship\n| image              = Don Blankenship Image (cropped).jpeg\n| alt                = Picture of Don Blankenship\n| caption            = Blankenship in 2010\n| birth_name         = Donald Leon Blankenship\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1950|3|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[Stopover, Kentucky]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Marshall University]] ([[Bachelor degree]])\n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Former CEO of [[Massey Energy]]<br>[[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster]]<br>West Virginia Republican primary Senate candidate\n| party              = [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Blankenship to wage third-party bid after losing primary|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/21/don-blankenship-third-party-constitution-party-600779|website=POLITICO}}</ref><br>[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (until 2018)<br>\n| module             = '''Criminal information'''{{Infobox criminal\n| child              = yes\n| criminal_charge    = Conspiracy to violate mine safety and health standards\n| criminal_penalty   = 1 year in federal prison<br>$250,000 fine\n}}\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|donblankenship.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Donald Leon Blankenship''' (born March 14, 1950) is an American business executive who was a candidate for the [[United States Senate]] in [[West Virginia]] in 2018. He was Chairman and [[CEO]] of the [[Massey Energy]] Company\u2014the sixth-largest [[coal]] company (by 2008 production) in the United States<ref name=\"EIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/coal/page/acr/table10.html|title=Major U.S. Coal Producers|date=September 18, 2009|publisher=[[Energy Information Administration]]|accessdate=April 7, 2010}}</ref>\u2014from 2000 until his retirement in 2010.<ref>T Allen, \"[http://blog.riskmetrics.com/gov/2010/12/investors-tour-role-in-massey-leadership-change.html Investors Tout Their Role in Massey's Leadership Change] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208020759/http://blog.riskmetrics.com/gov/2010/12/investors-tour-role-in-massey-leadership-change.html |date=February 8, 2011 }}\" (December 7, 2010) Riskmetrics</ref> \n\nOn December 3, 2015, Blankenship was found guilty of one misdemeanor charge of conspiring to willfully violate mine safety and health standards in relation to the [[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster|Upper Big Branch Mine explosion]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wchstv.com/news/features/eyewitness-news/stories/Jurors-Convict-Don-Blankenship-On-Conspiracy-Charge-238644.shtml |title=Jurors Convict Don Blankenship On Conspiracy Charge - WCHS - ABC |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205090625/http://www.wchstv.com/news/features/eyewitness-news/stories/Jurors-Convict-Don-Blankenship-On-Conspiracy-Charge-238644.shtml |archivedate=December 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> however the US Department of Justice's Office of Professional Responsibility later found that the prosecutors who worked to convict Blankenship failed to disclose sixty-one memoranda of witness interviews{{nbsp}} and thus committed reckless professional misconduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511531242-doj-says-prosecutors-in-blankenship-case-committed-misconduct|title=DOJ says prosecutors in Blankenship case committed misconduct|last=Asbury|first=Kyla|website=West Virginia Record|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\"Don Blankenship\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DonLBlankenship/posts/2133847020020233|title=Don Blankenship|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> Blankenship continues to claim his innocence,<ref name=\"Dickerson\">{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511382599-blankenship-says-doj-office-is-investigating-his-prosecution|title=Blankenship says DOJ office is investigating his prosecution|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donblankenship.com/view_post.php?id=86|title=Don Blankenship: American Competitionist|website=www.donblankenship.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=Don Blankenship Says Mine Tragedy That Killed 29 Isn't His Fault (HBO)|date=2017-09-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AyWHUdk2x_M|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> and has started to participate actively in local and state politics, after years of participating as a donor in his home state of [[West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Don_Blankenship.php |title=Newsmeat \u25b7 Don Blankenship's Federal Campaign Contribution Report |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020161103/http://newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Don_Blankenship.php |archivedate=October 20, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has frequently spoken out about politics, the environment, unions, and coal production. In [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018]], Blankenship lost a three-way Republican primary for the [[U.S. Senate]] to [[Patrick Morrisey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/patrick-morrisey-wins-west-virginia-gop-senate-primary|title=Patrick Morrisey Wins West Virginia GOP Senate Primary|work=Roll Call|first=Simone|last=Path\u00e9|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Citing false information, dirty politics and a personal unwillingness to quit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donblankenship.com/view_post.php?id=80|title=Don Blankenship: American Competitionist|website=www.donblankenship.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> Blankenship attempted to run as the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nominee but was unable to get on the ballot and later endorsed the Republican nominee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2018/05/21/politics/west-virginia-don-blankenship-third-party-senate-run/index.html|title=Still fighting McConnell, Don Blankenship launches third-party Senate bid in West Virginia|work=CNN|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>thehill.com May 21, 2018: [http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/388706-blankenship-third-party-bid-worries-senate-gop ''Blankenship third-party bid worries Senate GOP'']</ref>\n\nBlankenship launched his campaign in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as a member of the Constitution Party on October 18/19, 2019 during a meeting of the Constitution Party national committee.<ref name=launchcampaign1 />\n\n==Early life and education==\nBlankenship was born in [[Stopover, Kentucky]] and raised in [[Delorme, West Virginia]]. His father served in the [[Korean War]] and his mother, Nancy McCoy, was a member of the [[Hatfield\u2013McCoy feud|McCoy family]]. The two divorced soon after Don was born, and with her divorce settlement money Don's mother ran a convenience store and gas station for 40 years.<ref name=\"Shnayerson2008\">{{cite book|author=Michael Shnayerson|title=Coal River|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mUG6dO1P4CgC&pg=PA152|accessdate=September 1, 2012|date=January 8, 2008|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-374-12514-1|pages=152\u2013}}</ref> After graduating from [[Matewan High School]] in [[Matewan, West Virginia]] in 1968, Don earned a bachelor's degree in accounting from [[Marshall University]] in 1972 in just three school years, having worked as a union coal miner during summers and even taking a year off school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113980315809572248 |title=A Coal CEO's Unusual Pastime: Firing Up West Virginia Politics |author= Deborah Solomon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]], page A1 |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=May 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/business/x802979294/Blankenship-to-speak-at-energy-symposium |title=Blankenship to speak at energy symposium |publisher=The Herald Dispatch |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>Leamer 2013, p. 51.</ref> He was the recipient of Marshall University's \"Most Distinguished Alumni\" award and inducted into the Lewis College of Business Hall of Fame in 1999.<ref name=\"marshall1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marshall.edu/pressrelease.asp?ID=2872 |title=Marshall graduate pledges $300,000 for Medical School scholarships |publisher=Marshall.edu |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship is certified as a public accountant.<ref name=\"aicpa1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.williamsondailynews.com/view/full_story/2650489/article-Massey-CEO-to-speak-at-Tug-Valley-Chamber-banquet |title=The Williamson Daily News - Massey CEO to speak at Tug Valley Chamber banquet |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130209155442/http://www.williamsondailynews.com/view/full_story/2650489/article-Massey-CEO-to-speak-at-Tug-Valley-Chamber-banquet |archivedate=February 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2002, he was inducted into the [[American Institute of Certified Public Accountants]]' Business and Industry Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaahq.org/newsarc.cfm |title=American Accounting Association&nbsp;\u2014 News Archive |publisher=Aaahq.org |date= |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> and recognized by the West Virginia Society of Certified Public Accountants as an Outstanding Member in Business and Industry.<ref name=\"marshall1\"/> Blankenship was also inducted into the Tug Valley Mining Institute Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"aicpa1\"/>\n==Coal mining==\n===Massey Energy===\nBlankenship joined Massey Energy subsidiary Rawl Sales & Processing Co., in 1982. He went on to serve Massey Energy in a number of capacities.<ref name=\"businessweek2\">{{cite web|author=Stocks |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=658508&symbol=MEE |title=Stocks - Bloomberg |website=Investing.businessweek.com |date=2016-12-09 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Schelzig|first=Erik|url=http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |title=Virginia News &#124; WVEC.com &#124; News for Hampton Roads, Virginia |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110161925/http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archivedate=November 10, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He was promoted to president of Massey Coal Services, Inc. (1989\u20131991), then president and chief operating officer from 1990 to 1991.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite magazine|author=Don L. Blankenship |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=658508&symbol=MEE |title=Don Blankenship: Executive Profile & Biography  | magazine = Business Week |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> In 1992, Blankenship was named president, chairman of the board of A.T. Massey.<ref name=\"businessweek1\"/> He is the first non-Massey family member to be in charge of the company. When A.T. Massey was spun off from [[Fluor Corporation]] as Massey Energy in 2000,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.fluor.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=124955&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=134404&highlight= |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123073344/http://investor.fluor.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=124955&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=134404&highlight= |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-23 |title=Fluor Corporation - Investor Relations - Corporate News Release |website=Investor.fluor.com |accessdate=2016-12-30 }}</ref> Blankenship became the newly independent company's chairman and CEO. On December 3, 2010, Blankenship announced that he was retiring as CEO at the end of the year and would be succeeded by Massey President [[Baxter F. Phillips Jr]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Mario |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-03/massey-energy-says-don-blankenship-to-retire-as-chief-executive-dec-30.html |title=Massey's Blankenship to Retire Dec. 30, Be Replaced by President Phillips |publisher=Bloomberg |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=December 3, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship had a reputation for resistance to spending money, willingness to litigate for contract difficulties, and personally going into mines to persuade workers to abandon union organizing efforts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-04-10/massey-s-blankenship-fought-regulators-town-maid-as-coal-ceo.html |title=Massey's Blankenship Fought Regulators, Town, Maid as Coal CEO |magazine=Business Week |date=April 10, 2010 |accessdate=April 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413160009/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-04-10/massey-s-blankenship-fought-regulators-town-maid-as-coal-ceo.html |archivedate=April 13, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref> In a 1980s documentary, he said, \"It's like a jungle, where a jungle is survival of the fittest. Unions, communities, people\u2014everybody's gonna have to learn to accept that in the United States you have a capitalist society, and that capitalism, from a business standpoint, is survival of the most productive.\"<ref name=\"Destruction p. 168\">[[Chris Hedges]] and [[Joe Sacco]] (2012). ''Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt.'' p. 168. Nation Books. {{ISBN|1568586434}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Blankenship was elected to the board of directors of engineering and construction company [[Fluor Corporation]].<ref name=fluor>{{cite web| url=http://investor.fluor.com/news-releases/news-release-details/donald-l-blankenship-elected-fluor-board-directors| title=Donald L. Blankenship Elected to Flour Board of Directors| date=September 9, 1996| publisher=Flour}}</ref> He also serves as a director of the Center for Energy and Economic Development, a director of the [[National Mining Association]], Mission West Virginia Inc, and was on the [[U.S. Chamber of Commerce]] board of directors.<ref name=\"businessweek2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uschamber.com/about/board/all.htm |title=U.S. Chamber of Commerce - Board of Directors: U.S. Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030112113315/http://www.uschamber.com/about/board/all.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2003 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/preview/phoenix.zhtml?c=102864&p=irol-govBio&ID=140028 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705030850/http://phx.corporate-ir.net/preview/phoenix.zhtml?c=102864&p=irol-govBio&ID=140028 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 5, 2017 |title=Corporate Governance &#124;&#124; Massey Energy |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship was paid $17.8 million in 2009, the highest in the coal industry. It was a $6.8 million raise over 2008, and almost double his compensation package in 2007. Blankenship also received a [[deferred compensation]] package valued at $27.2 million in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Berkes |first=Howard |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126072828&ps=cprs |title=Massey CEO's Pay Soared As Mine Concerns Grew |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===McCoy Coal Group===\nIn 2011, Blankenship incorporated McCoy Coal Group, a coal company in [[Kentucky]] (not to be confused with the James River Coal Company subsidiary McCoy-Elkhorn Coal Corp). McCoy has yet to seek mining permits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wsaz.com/news/headlines/135259468.html |title=Don Blankenship Resurfaces, Forms Ky. Coal Company |website=Wsaz.com |date=2011-12-08 |accessdate=2016-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407033011/http://www.wsaz.com/news/headlines/135259468.html |archive-date=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nCiting his displeasure with federal handling of the coal industry, and his longtime criticisms of the condition of West Virginia politics in general, Blankenship ran for US Senate in the [[United States Senate elections, 2018|2018 Senate Election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/blankenship-west-virginia.html|title=Don Blankenship Loses West Virginia Republican Primary for Senate|last=Gabriel|first=Trip|date=2018-05-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship is an active participant in West Virginia politics.<ref name=PeopleVee>{{cite news|last1=Segal|first1=David|title=The People v. the Coal Baron|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/business/energy-environment/the-people-v-the-coal-baron.html?hpw&rref=business&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0|accessdate=June 21, 2015|date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> During a speech at the Tug Valley Mining Institute on November 20, 2008, Blankenship called House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]], Senator [[Harry Reid]] and former Vice President [[Al Gore]] \"crazies\" and \"greeniacs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0M_XbeXDNnM |title=The Big Lies Of Big Coal: Don Blankenship Speaks |publisher=YouTube |date=December 10, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship has spoken out against media coverage and false attacks by liberal media. He has also said \"the truth needs to be told about what happened at the Upper Big Branch coal mine\" on the basis that a single individual from the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration was chosen to investigate the disaster.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/05/17/don-blankenship-asked-trump-to-oppose-legislation-for-harsher-punishment-for-coal-mine-supervisors/| title=Don Blankenship asked Trump to oppose legislation for harsher punishment for coal mine supervisors| author=Lindsey Bever| date=17 May 2017| newspaper=The Washington Post| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> In a 1980s documentary, Blankenship stated about business, \"It's like a jungle, where a jungle is survival of the fittest. Unions, communities, people&nbsp;\u2014 everybody's gonna have to learn to accept that in the United States you have a capitalist society, and that capitalism, from a business standpoint, is survival of the most productive.\"<ref name=\"Destruction p. 168\"/>\n\n===Support of various advocacy groups===\nBlankenship supports [[Friends of Coal]], a West Virginia advocacy group founded as a countermeasure to environmental protection movements, in opposition to President Obama's \"war on coal\".<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/11/ex-con-coal-baron-don-blankenship-is-running-for-u-s-senate.html| title=Fresh Out of Prison, Reviled Coal Baron Don Blankenship Is Running for the U.S. Senate| author=Adam K. Raymond| date=29 November 2017| magazine=New York Magazine| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> He later released statements urging President Trump to avoid legislation enacting harsher punishment for coal mine supervisors that violate health and safety protocols, saying that \"coal supervisors are not criminals\", and that harsher laws would not improve mine safety.\n\nIn 2016, Blankenship supported conservative advocacy groups to remove Democrats from Legislature.<ref name=hd>{{cite web| url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/court-filing-sheds-more-light-on-blankenship-campaigns/article_9b3993bf-b29c-5969-96f6-ba8f5d6aa2e1.html| title=Court filing sheds more light on Blankenship campaigns| agency=Associated Press| date=14 October 2017| publisher=Herald Dispatch| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> That same year, Blankenship was criticized by Hillary Clinton's campaign after his appearance at her campaign stop in Williamson, West Virginia.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Clinton-responds-to-Don-Blankenship-showing-up-at-event-in-WVa-377969161.html| author=WSAZ News Staff| title=Blankenship issues statement after attending Clinton event| date=3 May 2016| publisher=WSAZ| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Climate change===\nBlankenship rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. In a speech at the Tug Valley Mining Institute, he said, \"I don't believe [[climate change]] is real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YEl7dF8N-ZU&e |title=Big Coal, Big Lies #1: Climate change does not exist |publisher=YouTube |date=December 9, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship reiterated his views on [[global warming]] in interviews with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] and ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Snyder |first=Jim |url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/68031-qaa-with-don-blankenship-ceo-of-massey-energy-co |title=Q&A with Don Blankenship, CEO of Massey Energy Co. - The Hill&nbsp;\u2014 covering Congress, Politics, Political Campaigns and Capitol Hill |publisher=TheHill.com |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/09/28/massey-coal-environment-business-washington-blankenship.html |title=Seeing Red On Cap And Trade |magazine=Forbes.com |date=September 28, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an October 30, 2009, letter to the editor of ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]'', Blankenship denied that climate change, or global warming, exists, and said, \"Why should we trust a report by the United Nations? The United Nations includes countries like Venezuela, North Korea and Iran.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coalzoom.com/article.cfm?articleid=343 |title=Charleston Gazette \u2013 Letter to the Editor from Don Blankenship |publisher=Coal Zoom |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref> According to Blankenship, \"the environmental movement isn't a great cause, it's a great business\", and in addition to lying about the Upper Big Branch mine disaster, the government has also lied \"about the science of global warming.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.thenation.com/article/disgraced-coal-baron-don-blankenship-rebrands-libertarian-activist/| author=Lee Fang| title=Disgraced Coal Baron Don Blankenship Rebrands As A Libertarian Activist| date=28 July 2014| magazine=The Nation| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, at a Senate campaign town hall, Blankenship said that \"climate change is probably a fact\", but added that American-made climate change is not, arguing that China's increase in coal production is the reason.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.register-herald.com/news/former-massey-ceo-puts-ubb-blame-on-msha-outlines-positions/article_2520cd12-34ca-566c-aa1a-c7223efdc564.html| title=Former Massey CEO puts UBB blame on MSHA; outlines positions at campaign town hall| author=Jessica Farish| date=25 January 2018| newspaper=The Register-Herald| access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Mine safety===\nAt a 2009 Labor Day rally in West Virginia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://friendsofamericarally.com/ |title=Friends of America Rally |publisher=Friends of America Rally |date=September 7, 2009 |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship said that federal and state mining regulators are ineffective at improving mine safety, and that the mining companies themselves are better suited to the task and should have less oversight,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climateprogress.org/2010/04/12/don-blankenship-mine-safety-regulators-silly-global-warming/ |title=Don Blankenship called safety regulators \"as silly as global warming\" \u00ab Climate Progress |publisher=Climateprogress.org |date=April 12, 2010 |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> saying, \"Washington and state politicians have no idea how to improve miners' safety.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://theweek.com/articles/495341/massey-disaster-coal-baron-don-blankenship-blame| title=The Massey disaster: Is 'Coal Baron' Don Blankenship to blame?| author=The Week Staff| date=9 April 2010| magazine=The Week| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore and during his 2018 Senate campaign, Blankenship blamed the federal regulators of the [[Mine Safety and Health Administration|MSHA]] for the Upper Big Branch Disaster for directing airflow targets in the mine.<ref name=\"Dickerson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theintelligencer.net/news/top-headlines/2018/03/senate-candidate-and-former-coal-ceo-don-blankenship-considers-conviction-a-badge-of-honor-in-west-virginia/ |title=Senate Candidate and Former Coal CEO Don Blankenship Blames MSHA, Considers Conviction A 'Badge of Honor' in West Virginia |publisher=The Intelligencer-Wheeling News-Register |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 United States Senate campaign===\nBlankenship entered the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] primary in the [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia,]] challenging incumbent Democratic U.S. Senator [[Joe Manchin]]. His television ads were aimed at \"getting the truth out\" about the Upper Big Branch explosion and \"exposing the government cover-up.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/11/ex-con-coal-baron-don-blankenship-is-running-for-u-s-senate.html| title=Fresh Out of Prison, Reviled Coal Baron Don Blankenship Is Running for the U.S. Senate| author=Adam K. Raymond| date=29 November 2017| magazine=New York Magazine| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref> The ads further claimed Blankenship had documents showing that the MSHA Upper Big Branch internal report was falsified and that the company was forced by the MSHA to use a defective ventilation system.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/dec/11/don-blankenship/convicted-w-va-mining-ceo-falsely-says-government-/| title=Convicted mining CEO and GOP candidate says official papers reveal 'Obama's deadliest cover-up'| author=Jon Greenberg| date=11 December 2017| publisher=Politifact| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/26/us/don-blankenship-west-virginia-senate.html| title=Coal Country Divides Over an Unrepentant Boss's Senate Bid| author=Trip Gabriel| date=26 February 2018| newspaper=The New York Times| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe also expressed a belief that Donald Trump's [[Executive Order 13767|proposed Mexico-United States border wall]] in conjunction ending sanctuary cities would help stop drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/don-blankenship-the-radical-republican-wants-to-be-wv-s/article_6f8ac8ea-5d6e-53b4-bca5-2fa1ca37566b.html| title=Don Blankenship, the 'radical' Republican, wants to be WV's conservative choice for Senate| author=Charles Young| date=25 March 2018| publisher=WVNews| access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship said he was \"Trumpier than Trump\" but that the establishment was misinforming him because they did not want him \"to be in the U.S. Senate and promote the president's agenda.\" The national Republican leadership and allied groups made statements and ran ads against Blankenship,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sanchez|first1=Luis|title=Blankenship: I'm Trumpier than Trump|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/386484-blankenship-im-trumpier-than-trump|website=The Hill|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> and the day before the Republican primary, Trump posted a tweet urging voters to vote for either of Blankenship's major primary opponents, [[Evan Jenkins (politician)|Evan Jenkins]] and [[Patrick Morrisey]], because Blankenship would not be competitive in the general election.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/07/politics/donald-trump-west-virginia-don-blankenship/index.html|title=Trump urges West Virginia voters to reject Blankenship|author1=Dan Merica |author2=Maegan Vazquez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Trump's tweet came in the wake of reporting that internal Republican polling had shown a surge in Blankenship's support among likely primary voters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/05/blankenship-polls-west-virginia-senate-primary-570752|title=Blankenship surging on eve of West Virginia Senate primary|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, whom Blankenship harshly criticized in his campaign, reportedly urged Trump to express opposition to Blankenship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/us/politics/don-blankenship-trump-west-virginia.html|title=Trump Weighs In on West Virginia Senate Race in Sign of Republican Anxiety|date=2018-05-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Republican primary campaign, Blankenship received criticism for calling McConnell's wife a \"[[Chinaman (term)|China person]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/04/don-blankenship-has-taken-opposition-to-political-correctness-to-a-new-extreme-and-thats-dangerous-for-the-gop/|title=Analysis {{!}} Don Blankenship has taken opposition to political correctness to a new extreme, and that's dangerous for the GOP|last=Scott|first=Eugene|date=4 May 2018|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/chinaperson-and-the-sanitization-of-a-racial-slur/558989/|title='Chinaperson' and the Sanitization of a Racial Slur|last=Zimmer|first=Ben|date=2018-04-26|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/02/politics/don-blankenship-defense-west-virginia-debate/index.html|title=GOP Senate candidate says 'wealthy Chinaperson' comment isn't racist|first=Maegan |last=Vazquez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Patrick Morrisey]] won the primary, Blankenship reentered the race as the nominee of the West Virginia Constitution Party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=CARNEY|first1=JORDAIN|last2=KAMISAR|first2=BEN|title=Blankenship third-party bid worries Senate GOP|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/388706-blankenship-third-party-bid-worries-senate-gop|website=The Hill|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mufson|first1=Steven|title=Spurned by Trump and GOP, coal baron Don Blankenship seeks a second chance in West Virginia|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/spurned-by-trump-and-gop-coal-baron-don-blankenship-seeks-a-second-chance-in-west-virginia/2018/05/22/27cd16a4-522d-11e8-9c91-7dab596e8252_story.html?noredirect=on|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his campaign he made a claim that the Upper Big Branch explosion was caused by the negligence of Mine Safety and Health Administration officials.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://grist.org/briefly/don-blankenship-fresh-outta-federal-prison-has-outlined-his-campaign-platform/| title=The 'Ship Has Sailed| author=Zoya Teirstein| date=26 January 2018| publisher=Grist| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wvva.com/story/37001058/2017/12/Tuesday/don-blankenship-explains-decision-to-run-for-us-senate| title=Don Blankenship explains U.S. Senate run| date=5 December 2017| publisher=WVVA| access-date=11 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412001400/http://www.wvva.com/story/37001058/2017/12/Tuesday/don-blankenship-explains-decision-to-run-for-us-senate| archive-date=April 12, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2020 presidential campaign===\n[[File:Don Blankenship 20210 (75220642).jpg|thumb|Bankenship presidential campaign logo]]\nBlankenship launched his campaign for the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nomination in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] in October 2019 during a meeting of the Constitution Party national committee.<ref name=launchcampaign1>{{cite web| url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/10/20/don-blankenship-speaks-at-constitution-party-national-committee-meeting/|title=Don Blankenship declares for Constitution Party presidential nomination|website=Ballot Access News|date=October 20, 2019|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBlankenship has two children.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last1=Schelzig |first=Erik |url=http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929125507/http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archivedate=September 29, 2008 |title=Virginia News &#124; WVEC.com &#124; News for Hampton Roads, Virginia |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2016-12-30 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He was profiled in a 2005 [[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]] documentary, ''The Kingmaker''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=91CN9KsjSy8|title=The Kingmaker|via=YouTube|publisher=West Virginia Public Broadcasting}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Deborah May===\nA former employee of Blankenship, Deborah May, similarly filed a lawsuit claiming that stress from personal abuse forced her to quit her job in November 2005. The lawsuit claimed that such comparatively minor mistakes as a wrong breakfast order from [[McDonald's]], misplaced ice cream in the freezer, and an improperly hung jacket in the closet caused difficulties with Blankenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/justices-hear-unemployment-appeal-from-ex-maid-to-blankenship/article_c784c684-15eb-5fe1-83a9-dc476b8f2b0c.html|title=Justices hear unemployment appeal from ex-maid to Blankenship|last=|first=|date=1 April 2008|website=The Herald-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In June 2008, West Virginia's top court ruled that May was entitled to unemployment benefits because \"the unrefuted evidence\" showed that Blankenship \"physically grabbed\" the maid, threw food after she brought back the wrong fast-food order, and tore a tie rack and coat hanger out of a closet after she forgot to leave the hanger out for his coat. \"This shocking conduct\" showed May was in effect fired because she felt compelled to quit, the justices said.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_17/b4175048798671.htm |title=Massey Energy: The Accountant of Coal |last=Fisk |first=Margaret Cronin |last2= Sullivan |first2=Brian K. |date=April 15, 2010|magazine=BusinessWeek |access-date=April 15, 2010 |last3=Freifeld |first3=Karen }}</ref>\n\n===Upper Big Branch explosion===\n{{main|Upper Big Branch Mine disaster}}\nOn April 5, 2010 an [[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster|explosion at Massey's Upper Big Branch mine]] killed 29 miners. It was the worst U.S. coal mining disaster since 1970, when an explosion killed 38 in [[Hyden, Kentucky]]. [[NPR]] reported Massey executive Stanley Suboleski as saying that MSHA ordered airflow changes, made hours before the explosion, \"were changes the company opposed but complied with anyway.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126884971|title=Mine Probe Examines Airflow, Possible Tampering|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref> On April 12, [[New York State Comptroller]] [[Thomas DiNapoli]], trustee of the [[New York State Common Retirement Fund]] which held 303,550 shares of Massey stock, called for Blankenship to resign immediately. \"This tragedy was a failure both of risk management and effective board oversight. Blankenship must step down and make room for more responsible leadership at Massey.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Steve James |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63C2Q920100413 |title=Massey faces shareholder anger over mine disaster |work=Reuters |date= April 13, 2010|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> On April 22, Massey Energy's lead independent director [[Bobby Ray Inman|Bobby R. Inman]] announced that \"Blankenship has the full support and confidence of the Massey Energy Board of Directors.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/coal-boss-don-blankenship-full-support-massey-energy/story?id=10451791 |title=Coal Boss Don Blankenship Has Full Support of Massey Energy Board - ABC News |website=Abcnews.go.com |date=2010-04-22 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> On April 25, President [[Barack Obama]], Vice President [[Joe Biden]], and state officials paid tribute to the 29 coal miners at a memorial service in [[Beckley, West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/04/obama-eulogizes-29-miners-----dont-let-this-happen-again/1 |title=Obama eulogizes 29 W.Va. miners - 'Don't let this happen again' |website=Content.usatoday.com |date=2010-04-25 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref>\n\n\"Prosecutors said Massey manipulated the ventilation system during inspections of the Upper Big Branch mine to fool safety officials and disabled a methane monitor on a cutting machine a few months before the explosion on April 5, 2010....<ref>{{cite web|author=John Raby|url=http://www.rdmag.com/News/FeedsAP/2012/03/materials-ex-mine-leader-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-us-blast/ |title=Ex-mine leader pleads guilty in deadly US blast &#124; R&D Mag |publisher=Rdmag.com |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=September 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141203012554/http://www.rdmag.com/News/FeedsAP/2012/03/materials-ex-mine-leader-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-us-blast |archivedate=December 3, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> In March 2013 Blankenship was directly implicated in conspiring to skirt safety regulations when a former Massey Energy official accused Blankenship of conspiring and plotting to hide safety violations from federal safety inspectors. The implication was that Blankenship would order his officials to warn mine operators when the federal inspectors were coming for \"surprise\" visits, and to quickly cover up any safety violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecontributor.com/don-blankenship-dark-lord-coal-country-implicated-upper-big-branch-mine-explosion-deaths|title=Coal Baron Don Blankenship Implicated In The Death Of 29 Miners|publisher=The Contributor|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship was convicted of a single misdemeanor charge of conspiring to violate federal mine safety standards and went on to serve a one-year prison sentence. He called himself a \"political prisoner\", feuded with United States Senator [[Joe Manchin]] and the [[Mine Safety and Health Administration]] (MSHA) over the explosion,<ref>{{cite news|last=Raby|first=John|date=May 11, 2017|title=Coal exec convicted in miner deaths is released from prison, immediately lashes out on Twitter|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-don-blankenship-mine-executive-20170511-story.html|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> considered running against Manchin for the Senate,<ref>{{cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Jeff|date=July 13, 2017|title=Blankenship: Senate run \"a possibility\"|work=MetroNews|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2017/07/13/blankenship-senate-run-a-possibility/|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> and called for a new investigation into the explosion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kercheval|first=Hoppy|date=September 8, 2017|title=My end of the week notes|work=MetroNews|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2017/09/08/my-end-of-the-week-notes/|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> On May 25, 2017, he formally appealed his case to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]]. His petition argued that the U.S. District Court in Charleston and the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Virginia, \"both erred in rulings, and they claim Blankenship was a victim of politics.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511120601-blankenship-s-legal-team-files-appeal-petition-with-u-s-supreme-court|title=Blankenship's legal team files appeal petition with U.S. Supreme Court|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|date=2017-05-26|work=West Virginia Record|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Blankenship funded a television ad featuring the sister of one of the miners killed in the Upper Big Branch coal mine explosion. The sister, Gwen Thomas, asks in the ad \"if the United States Mine Safety and Health Administration insisted that changes be made which reduced Upper Big Branch's airflow before the explosion.\" She asks the government to publicly release the gas analyses taken after the explosion, and she asks for help from President Donald Trump and U.S. Senators Joe Manchin (D-WV) and Shelley Moore Capito (R-WV) in getting answers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511188274-sister-of-upper-big-branch-miner-featured-in-television-ad|title=Sister of Upper Big Branch miner featured in television ad|last=Asbury|first=Kyla|date=2017-08-18|work=West Virginia Record|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en}}</ref> The US Center for Disease Control's (CDC) National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) found that the initial explosion could have been prevented by MSHA forcing Massey to avoid a build up of gas, and that subsequent injury could have been prevented by forcing Massey to avoid build up of coal dust.<ref name=\":0\"/> The NIOSH's page on Mining, says that to avoid Methane buildup \"Large fans circulate air in mines to provide ventilation to the working areas.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/mining/features/coalmineexplosion.html|title=Coal Mine Explosion Prevention|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Blankenship for Senate released a statement outlining a finding of the Department of Justice's [[Office of Professional Responsibility]] (DOJ-OPR) which had investigated [[Booth Goodwin]] and [[Steve Ruby]], the prosecuting attorney's in Blankenship's federal trial. The DOJ-OPR found that both prosecutors were responsible for \"recklessly\" disregarding their discovery obligations. According to the release, at least 61 memoranda of witness interviews were not provided to Blankenship's defense team, and Blankenship's attorney believes these showed Blankenship had done nothing illegal.<ref name=\"Don Blankenship\"/>\n\n===Groundwater===\nBlankenship has been accused of withholding knowledge of pollution. According to accusations made in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', groundwater pollution from coal slurry injection by Massey Energy was contaminating wells around Blankenship's home. Blankenship had a water line built to his home from a nearby town. According to the accusation, Blankenship did not offer to provide uncontaminated water to any of his neighbors, and failed to inform them of any problem.<ref>[[Jeff Goodell|Goodell, Jeff]] (November 11, 2010). [https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/17390/236336?RS_show_page=4 Don Blankenship: The Dark Lord of Coal Country]. ''[[Rolling Stone]].'' Retrieved December 10, 2010</ref>\n\n===Campaign against Warren McGraw===\nIn 2004, Blankenship contributed $3 million to the \"And For The Sake of the Kids\" PAC, campaigning against the reelection of [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia|West Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice [[Warren McGraw]]. [[Brent Benjamin]] went on to defeat McGraw in the general election. Speaking about the election, Blankenship said, \"I helped defeat a judge who had released a pedophile to work in a local school, who had driven doctors out of state, and who had cost workers their jobs for thirty plus years. I think this effort helped unchain West Virginia's economy and benefited working families.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/10/idUS159711+10-Jun-2009+PRN20090610 |title=Don L. Blankenship Addresses the U.S. Supreme Court Ruling on Caperton v. A.T. Massey... |work=Reuters |date=June 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114051011/http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/10/idUS159711+10-Jun-2009+PRN20090610|archivedate=14 November 2012 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' called Blankenship's ads \"venomous.\"<ref name=\"usatoday1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20090303/editorial03_st.art.htm |title=Mining case shows sooty side of big-money judicial elections |date=March 2, 2009 |access-date=April 6, 2010 |newspaper=USA TODAY}}</ref> According to a ''USA Today'' editorial dated March 3, 2009, Blankenship \"vividly illustrated how big money corrupts judicial elections. It puts justice up for sale to the highest bidder.\"<ref name=\"usatoday1\"/>\n\nNotably, Blankenship's coal company [[Massey Energy|Massey Coal]] had recently lost a civil case in West Virginia state court prior to the judicial campaign and had been ordered to pay a $50 million judgment. Blakenship's case was pending on appeal as he sponsored Brent Benjamin's campaign for a seat on the West Virginia Supreme Court. When the case was taken up on appeal, Benjamin was one of the judges in a position to decide the case. The plaintiff requested that Benjamin recuse himself owing to a conflict of interest stemming from Blakenship's contributions to his campaign, but he refused. Benjamin ultimately cast a decisive vote to vacate the lower court's judgment in a 3\u20132 decision. In [[Caperton v. A.T. Massey Coal Co.]], the Supreme Court ruled that Benjamin's refusal to recuse himself in light of such an obvious conflict of interest constituted a violation of the plaintiff's constitutional right to due process and remanded the case to the West Virginia Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2008/08-22|title=Caperton v. A. T. Massey Coal Co.|last=|first=|date=|website=Oyez|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] political journalist [[Michael Tomasky]], also a native West Virginian, claimed that Blankenship was \"famous in West Virginia as the man who successfully bought himself a State Supreme Court Justice in 2004 and then tried to buy himself the state legislature, failing spectacularly at the latter effort.\"<ref name=\"tomasky\">Tomasky, Michael, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/21802 \"Night Comes to the Appalachians\"] ''[[New York Review of Books]]'', Volume 55, Number 14; September 25, 2008.</ref> In his 2008 book ''[[Coal River (book)|Coal River]]'', Michael Shnayerson reports that no such foundation was ever set up.<ref>Shnayerson, Michael (2008), ''Coal River'', New York, New York: [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]]</ref> Although Blankenship was the primary donor to \"And For the Sake of Kids,\" other groups, including Doctors for Justice, contributed over $1 million to ASK. Another group, Citizens for Quality Health Care, funded in part by the West Virginia Chamber of Commerce, spent over $350,000 to defeat McGraw.<ref>Nyden, Paul (January 7, 2005, Charleston Gazette), \"Coal, Doctor's Groups Donated to Anti-McGraw Effort.\"</ref> Meanwhile, several groups spent millions opposing Benjamin and supporting McGraw, including West Virginia Consumers for Justice and Hugh Caperton, CEO of Harmon Development Corporation.<ref>O'Brien, John (West Virginia Record January 24, 2008) \"Caperton was Anti-Benjamin from the Start.\"</ref> Blankenship is featured in [[Laurence Leamer]]'s 2013 book ''The Price of Justice: A True Story of Greed and Corruption''<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-8050-9471-8 |title=Nonfiction Book Review: The Price of Justice: A True Story of Two Lawyers' Epic Battle Against Corruption and Greed in Coal Country |author=Laurence Leamer |isbn=978-0-8050-9471-8 |website=Publishersweekly.com |date=2013-03-18 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> and in Peter Galuszka's 2012 book ''Thunder on the Mountain: Death at Massey and the Dirty Secrets Behind Big Coal''.<ref>{{Cite book |title= Thunder on the Mountain: Death at Massey and the Dirty Secrets Behind Big Coal |last=Galuszka |first=Peter A. |date=2012-09-18 |isbn=978-1-250-00021-7 }}</ref>\n\n===Conflict of interest with Spike Maynard===\nOn January 15, 2008, photographs of Blankenship vacationing on the French Riviera with [[West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals|West Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice [[Spike Maynard]], while Massey had a case pending before that court, appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/15/us/15court.html | work=The New York Times | title=Motion Ties W. Virginia Justice to Coal Executive | first=Adam | last=Liptak | date=January 15, 2008}}</ref> On April 3, 2008, ''[[ABC News]]'' reported that Blankenship attacked an ''ABC News'' photographer at a Massey facility near [[Belfry, Kentucky]] as the photographer attempted to question Blankenship about the photos. \"If you're going to start taking pictures of me, you're liable to get shot!\" Blankenship stated in the video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=4582452&page=1 |title=Coal Boss: If You Take Photos, 'You're Liable to Get Shot' |publisher=ABC News |date=April 3, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Maynard later lost his bid for reelection to the West Virginia Supreme Court in the primary election.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/15/us/15judge.html?pagewanted=print | work=The New York Times | title=West Virginia's Top Judge Loses His Re-election Bid | first=Ian | last=Urbina | date=May 15, 2008}}</ref> On February 14, 2009, Blankenship told ''The New York Times'', \"I've been around West Virginia long enough to know that politicians don't stay bought, particularly ones that are going to be in office for 12 years... So I would never go out and spend money to try to gain favor with a politician. Eliminating a bad politician makes sense. Electing somebody hoping he's going to be in your favor doesn't make any sense at all.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/15/washington/15scotus.html?ref=washington | work=The New York Times | title=Case May Alter Judge Elections Across Country | first=Adam | last=Liptak | date=February 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Comments on Mitch McConnell===\nIn April 2018, Blankenship released an ad in which he calls [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] \"cocaine Mitch\", urging potential voters to \"ditch\" McConnell.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Samuels|first1=Brett|title=Blankenship releases ad calling McConnell 'cocaine Mitch'|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/385574-blankenship-releases-ad-calling-mcconnell-cocaine-mitch|website=The Hill|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, he released another ad attacking McConnell, his wife, [[Elaine Chao]], and his in-laws as his \"[[Chinaman (term)|China family]]\", and again called McConnell \"cocaine Mitch\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/03/blankenship-mcconnell-china-568305 |title=Blankenship goes after McConnell's 'China family' in new ad |last=Isenstadt |first=Alex |date=May 3, 2018 |work=POLITICO |access-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Times McConnell\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/us/politics/don-blankenship-china-west-virginia.html|title=Don Blankenship, West Virginia Candidate, Lives Near Las Vegas and Mulled Chinese Citizenship|date=2018-04-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The premise of the moniker was that McConnell's father-in-law owns a shipping company that in 2014 was found to have {{Convert|90|lb}} of cocaine on one of its vessels set to leave Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/5/7/17326708/cocaine-mitch-mcconnell-don-blankenship|title=Cocaine Mitch: Don Blankenship's factually dubious attack on McConnell, explained|publisher=Vox|first=Andrew|last=Prokop|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> The Colombian authorities did not accuse the company of conspiring to transport the cocaine, and the company was never investigated for the matter. McConnell, who has no role in the operation of his father-in-law's shipping business, was never suspected by any authorities of having any involvement in the incident. The ''Washington Post''<nowiki/>'s Fact Checker column investigated the \"cocaine Mitch\" claims and gave them a \"Four Pinocchios\" rating, concluding that \"Blankenship has no evidence to support his crude and incendiary attack.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2018/05/04/the-kooky-tale-of-cocaine-mitch/|title=Analysis {{!}} The kooky tale of 'Cocaine Mitch'|last=Rizzo|first=Salvador|date=2018-05-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> After Blankenship lost his primary race, an official campaign account for McConnell posted a photoshopped picture of McConnell surrounded by a cloud of cocaine dust with the accompanying text, \"Thanks for playing, Don.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Team_Mitch/status/994036999387537409|title=Thanks for playing, @DonBlankenship. #WVSen|website=Twitter|date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> The picture was based on promotional materials for the [[Netflix]] TV show ''[[Narcos]]''.\n\nWhen asked if Blankenship's rhetoric in the \"China Family\" political ad was racist, McConnell suggested that his answer would depend on the results of the Republican primary election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/mcconnell-blankenship-racist-west-virginia-republican-senate-primary.html|title=McConnell Won't Say if Blankenship Is Racist Until He Knows Election Result.|work=NYMag|first= Jonathan |last=Chait|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> When pressed on the ad's alleged racism, Blankenship said that his ad was not racist because the Chinese are not a race. He said, \"Races are Negro, White Caucasian, Hispanic, and Asian.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sfpathe/status/992202466648383488|title=Asked @DonBlankenship about his new ad being racist. Here's what he told me... #WVSEN|website=Twitter|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2018/05/don-blankenship-uses-negro-in-race-discussion-after-china-person-ad.html|title=Ex-Con West Virginia Senate Candidate Uses the Word \"Negro\" While Defending TV Ad About \"China People\"|last=Mathis-Lilley|first=Ben|work=Slate Magazine|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{citation|last=Leamer|first=Laurence|title=The Price of Justice: A True Story of Greed and Corruption|place=New York|publisher=Times Books|isbn=9780805094718|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieCShJpT7y8C|date=May 7, 2013}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.votedonblankenship.com/ Vote on Blankenship, Official 2018 US Senate campaign website]\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blankenship, Don}}\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American male criminals]]\n[[Category:Anti-Chinese sentiment in the United States]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Marshall University alumni]]\n[[Category:Massey Energy]]\n[[Category:People from Pike County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Williamson, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Constitutionalists]]\n[[Category:West Virginia politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:West Virginia Republicans]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Don Blankenship\n| image              = Don Blankenship Image (cropped).jpeg\n| alt                = Picture of Don Blankenship\n| caption            = Blankenship in 2010\n| birth_name         = Donald Leon Blankenship\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1950|3|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[Stopover, Kentucky]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Marshall University]] ([[Bachelor degree]])\n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Former CEO of [[Massey Energy]]<br>[[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster]]<br>West Virginia Republican primary Senate candidate\n| party              = [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|title=Blankenship to wage third-party bid after losing primary|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/21/don-blankenship-third-party-constitution-party-600779|website=POLITICO}}</ref><br>[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (until 2018)<br>\n| module             = '''Criminal information'''{{Infobox criminal\n| child              = yes\n| criminal_charge    = Conspiracy to violate mine safety and health standards\n| criminal_penalty   = 1 year in federal prison<br>$250,000 fine\n}}\n| spouse             = \n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{url|donblankenship.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Donald Leon Blankenship''' (born March 14, 1950) is an American business executive who was a candidate for the [[United States Senate]] in [[West Virginia]] in 2018. He was Chairman and [[CEO]] of the [[Massey Energy]] Company\u2014the sixth-largest [[coal]] company (by 2008 production) in the United States<ref name=\"EIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/coal/page/acr/table10.html|title=Major U.S. Coal Producers|date=September 18, 2009|publisher=[[Energy Information Administration]]|accessdate=April 7, 2010}}</ref>\u2014from 2000 until his retirement in 2010.<ref>T Allen, \"[http://blog.riskmetrics.com/gov/2010/12/investors-tour-role-in-massey-leadership-change.html Investors Tout Their Role in Massey's Leadership Change] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208020759/http://blog.riskmetrics.com/gov/2010/12/investors-tour-role-in-massey-leadership-change.html |date=February 8, 2011 }}\" (December 7, 2010) Riskmetrics</ref> \n\nOn December 3, 2015, Blankenship was found guilty of one misdemeanor charge of conspiring to willfully violate mine safety and health standards in relation to the [[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster|Upper Big Branch Mine explosion]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wchstv.com/news/features/eyewitness-news/stories/Jurors-Convict-Don-Blankenship-On-Conspiracy-Charge-238644.shtml |title=Jurors Convict Don Blankenship On Conspiracy Charge - WCHS - ABC |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205090625/http://www.wchstv.com/news/features/eyewitness-news/stories/Jurors-Convict-Don-Blankenship-On-Conspiracy-Charge-238644.shtml |archivedate=December 5, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> however the US Department of Justice's Office of Professional Responsibility later found that the prosecutors who worked to convict Blankenship failed to disclose sixty-one memoranda of witness interviews{{nbsp}} and thus committed reckless professional misconduct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511531242-doj-says-prosecutors-in-blankenship-case-committed-misconduct|title=DOJ says prosecutors in Blankenship case committed misconduct|last=Asbury|first=Kyla|website=West Virginia Record|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\"Don Blankenship\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DonLBlankenship/posts/2133847020020233|title=Don Blankenship|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> Blankenship continues to claim his innocence,<ref name=\"Dickerson\">{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511382599-blankenship-says-doj-office-is-investigating-his-prosecution|title=Blankenship says DOJ office is investigating his prosecution|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donblankenship.com/view_post.php?id=86|title=Don Blankenship: American Competitionist|website=www.donblankenship.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=Don Blankenship Says Mine Tragedy That Killed 29 Isn't His Fault (HBO)|date=2017-09-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AyWHUdk2x_M|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> and has started to participate actively in local and state politics, after years of participating as a donor in his home state of [[West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Don_Blankenship.php |title=Newsmeat \u25b7 Don Blankenship's Federal Campaign Contribution Report |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020161103/http://newsmeat.com/ceo_political_donations/Don_Blankenship.php |archivedate=October 20, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has frequently spoken out about politics, the environment, unions, and coal production. In [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018]], Blankenship lost a three-way Republican primary for the [[U.S. Senate]] to [[Patrick Morrisey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/patrick-morrisey-wins-west-virginia-gop-senate-primary|title=Patrick Morrisey Wins West Virginia GOP Senate Primary|work=Roll Call|first=Simone|last=Path\u00e9|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Citing false information, dirty politics and a personal unwillingness to quit,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donblankenship.com/view_post.php?id=80|title=Don Blankenship: American Competitionist|website=www.donblankenship.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> Blankenship attempted to run as the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nominee but was unable to get on the ballot and later endorsed the Republican nominee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2018/05/21/politics/west-virginia-don-blankenship-third-party-senate-run/index.html|title=Still fighting McConnell, Don Blankenship launches third-party Senate bid in West Virginia|work=CNN|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>thehill.com May 21, 2018: [http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/388706-blankenship-third-party-bid-worries-senate-gop ''Blankenship third-party bid worries Senate GOP'']</ref>\n\nBlankenship launched his campaign in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as a member of the Constitution Party on October 18/19, 2019 during a meeting of the Constitution Party national committee.<ref name=launchcampaign1>{{cite web| url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/10/20/don-blankenship-speaks-at-constitution-party-national-committee-meeting/|title=Don Blankenship declares for Constitution Party presidential nomination|website=ballot-access.org|date=October 20, 2019|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBlankenship was born in [[Stopover, Kentucky]] and raised in [[Delorme, West Virginia]]. His father served in the [[Korean War]] and his mother, Nancy McCoy, was a member of the [[Hatfield\u2013McCoy feud|McCoy family]]. The two divorced soon after Don was born, and with her divorce settlement money Don's mother ran a convenience store and gas station for 40 years.<ref name=\"Shnayerson2008\">{{cite book|author=Michael Shnayerson|title=Coal River|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mUG6dO1P4CgC&pg=PA152|accessdate=September 1, 2012|date=January 8, 2008|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-374-12514-1|pages=152\u2013}}</ref> After graduating from [[Matewan High School]] in [[Matewan, West Virginia]] in 1968, Don earned a bachelor's degree in accounting from [[Marshall University]] in 1972 in just three school years, having worked as a union coal miner during summers and even taking a year off school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113980315809572248 |title=A Coal CEO's Unusual Pastime: Firing Up West Virginia Politics |author= Deborah Solomon |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]], page A1 |date=February 13, 2006 |accessdate=May 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/business/x802979294/Blankenship-to-speak-at-energy-symposium |title=Blankenship to speak at energy symposium |publisher=The Herald Dispatch |date=October 23, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>Leamer 2013, p. 51.</ref> He was the recipient of Marshall University's \"Most Distinguished Alumni\" award and inducted into the Lewis College of Business Hall of Fame in 1999.<ref name=\"marshall1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marshall.edu/pressrelease.asp?ID=2872 |title=Marshall graduate pledges $300,000 for Medical School scholarships |publisher=Marshall.edu |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship is certified as a public accountant.<ref name=\"aicpa1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.williamsondailynews.com/view/full_story/2650489/article-Massey-CEO-to-speak-at-Tug-Valley-Chamber-banquet |title=The Williamson Daily News - Massey CEO to speak at Tug Valley Chamber banquet |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130209155442/http://www.williamsondailynews.com/view/full_story/2650489/article-Massey-CEO-to-speak-at-Tug-Valley-Chamber-banquet |archivedate=February 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2002, he was inducted into the [[American Institute of Certified Public Accountants]]' Business and Industry Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aaahq.org/newsarc.cfm |title=American Accounting Association&nbsp;\u2014 News Archive |publisher=Aaahq.org |date= |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> and recognized by the West Virginia Society of Certified Public Accountants as an Outstanding Member in Business and Industry.<ref name=\"marshall1\"/> Blankenship was also inducted into the Tug Valley Mining Institute Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"aicpa1\"/>\n==Coal mining==\n===Massey Energy===\nBlankenship joined Massey Energy subsidiary Rawl Sales & Processing Co., in 1982. He went on to serve Massey Energy in a number of capacities.<ref name=\"businessweek2\">{{cite web|author=Stocks |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=658508&symbol=MEE |title=Stocks - Bloomberg |website=Investing.businessweek.com |date=2016-12-09 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Schelzig|first=Erik|url=http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |title=Virginia News &#124; WVEC.com &#124; News for Hampton Roads, Virginia |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110161925/http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archivedate=November 10, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He was promoted to president of Massey Coal Services, Inc. (1989\u20131991), then president and chief operating officer from 1990 to 1991.<ref name=\"businessweek1\">{{cite magazine|author=Don L. Blankenship |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=658508&symbol=MEE |title=Don Blankenship: Executive Profile & Biography  | magazine = Business Week |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> In 1992, Blankenship was named president, chairman of the board of A.T. Massey.<ref name=\"businessweek1\"/> He is the first non-Massey family member to be in charge of the company. When A.T. Massey was spun off from [[Fluor Corporation]] as Massey Energy in 2000,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.fluor.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=124955&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=134404&highlight= |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123073344/http://investor.fluor.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=124955&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=134404&highlight= |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-23 |title=Fluor Corporation - Investor Relations - Corporate News Release |website=Investor.fluor.com |accessdate=2016-12-30 }}</ref> Blankenship became the newly independent company's chairman and CEO. On December 3, 2010, Blankenship announced that he was retiring as CEO at the end of the year and would be succeeded by Massey President [[Baxter F. Phillips Jr]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parker |first=Mario |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-03/massey-energy-says-don-blankenship-to-retire-as-chief-executive-dec-30.html |title=Massey's Blankenship to Retire Dec. 30, Be Replaced by President Phillips |publisher=Bloomberg |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=December 3, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship had a reputation for resistance to spending money, willingness to litigate for contract difficulties, and personally going into mines to persuade workers to abandon union organizing efforts.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-04-10/massey-s-blankenship-fought-regulators-town-maid-as-coal-ceo.html |title=Massey's Blankenship Fought Regulators, Town, Maid as Coal CEO |magazine=Business Week |date=April 10, 2010 |accessdate=April 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413160009/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-04-10/massey-s-blankenship-fought-regulators-town-maid-as-coal-ceo.html |archivedate=April 13, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref> In a 1980s documentary, he said, \"It's like a jungle, where a jungle is survival of the fittest. Unions, communities, people\u2014everybody's gonna have to learn to accept that in the United States you have a capitalist society, and that capitalism, from a business standpoint, is survival of the most productive.\"<ref name=\"Destruction p. 168\">[[Chris Hedges]] and [[Joe Sacco]] (2012). ''Days of Destruction, Days of Revolt.'' p. 168. Nation Books. {{ISBN|1568586434}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Blankenship was elected to the board of directors of engineering and construction company [[Fluor Corporation]].<ref name=fluor>{{cite web| url=http://investor.fluor.com/news-releases/news-release-details/donald-l-blankenship-elected-fluor-board-directors| title=Donald L. Blankenship Elected to Flour Board of Directors| date=September 9, 1996| publisher=Flour}}</ref> He also serves as a director of the Center for Energy and Economic Development, a director of the [[National Mining Association]], Mission West Virginia Inc, and was on the [[U.S. Chamber of Commerce]] board of directors.<ref name=\"businessweek2\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uschamber.com/about/board/all.htm |title=U.S. Chamber of Commerce - Board of Directors: U.S. Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=2017-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030112113315/http://www.uschamber.com/about/board/all.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2003 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/preview/phoenix.zhtml?c=102864&p=irol-govBio&ID=140028 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705030850/http://phx.corporate-ir.net/preview/phoenix.zhtml?c=102864&p=irol-govBio&ID=140028 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 5, 2017 |title=Corporate Governance &#124;&#124; Massey Energy |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship was paid $17.8 million in 2009, the highest in the coal industry. It was a $6.8 million raise over 2008, and almost double his compensation package in 2007. Blankenship also received a [[deferred compensation]] package valued at $27.2 million in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|last=Berkes |first=Howard |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126072828&ps=cprs |title=Massey CEO's Pay Soared As Mine Concerns Grew |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===McCoy Coal Group===\nIn 2011, Blankenship incorporated McCoy Coal Group, a coal company in [[Kentucky]] (not to be confused with the James River Coal Company subsidiary McCoy-Elkhorn Coal Corp). McCoy has yet to seek mining permits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wsaz.com/news/headlines/135259468.html |title=Don Blankenship Resurfaces, Forms Ky. Coal Company |website=Wsaz.com |date=2011-12-08 |accessdate=2016-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407033011/http://www.wsaz.com/news/headlines/135259468.html |archive-date=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nCiting his displeasure with federal handling of the coal industry, and his longtime criticisms of the condition of West Virginia politics in general, Blankenship ran for US Senate in the [[United States Senate elections, 2018|2018 Senate Election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/blankenship-west-virginia.html|title=Don Blankenship Loses West Virginia Republican Primary for Senate|last=Gabriel|first=Trip|date=2018-05-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship is an active participant in West Virginia politics.<ref name=PeopleVee>{{cite news|last1=Segal|first1=David|title=The People v. the Coal Baron|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/business/energy-environment/the-people-v-the-coal-baron.html?hpw&rref=business&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0|accessdate=June 21, 2015|date=June 20, 2015}}</ref> During a speech at the Tug Valley Mining Institute on November 20, 2008, Blankenship called House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]], Senator [[Harry Reid]] and former Vice President [[Al Gore]] \"crazies\" and \"greeniacs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0M_XbeXDNnM |title=The Big Lies Of Big Coal: Don Blankenship Speaks |publisher=YouTube |date=December 10, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship has spoken out against media coverage and false attacks by liberal media. He has also said \"the truth needs to be told about what happened at the Upper Big Branch coal mine\" on the basis that a single individual from the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration was chosen to investigate the disaster.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/05/17/don-blankenship-asked-trump-to-oppose-legislation-for-harsher-punishment-for-coal-mine-supervisors/| title=Don Blankenship asked Trump to oppose legislation for harsher punishment for coal mine supervisors| author=Lindsey Bever| date=17 May 2017| newspaper=The Washington Post| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> In a 1980s documentary, Blankenship stated about business, \"It's like a jungle, where a jungle is survival of the fittest. Unions, communities, people&nbsp;\u2014 everybody's gonna have to learn to accept that in the United States you have a capitalist society, and that capitalism, from a business standpoint, is survival of the most productive.\"<ref name=\"Destruction p. 168\"/>\n\n===Support of various advocacy groups===\nBlankenship supports [[Friends of Coal]], a West Virginia advocacy group founded as a countermeasure to environmental protection movements, in opposition to President Obama's \"war on coal\".<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/11/ex-con-coal-baron-don-blankenship-is-running-for-u-s-senate.html| title=Fresh Out of Prison, Reviled Coal Baron Don Blankenship Is Running for the U.S. Senate| author=Adam K. Raymond| date=29 November 2017| magazine=New York Magazine| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> He later released statements urging President Trump to avoid legislation enacting harsher punishment for coal mine supervisors that violate health and safety protocols, saying that \"coal supervisors are not criminals\", and that harsher laws would not improve mine safety.\n\nIn 2016, Blankenship supported conservative advocacy groups to remove Democrats from Legislature.<ref name=hd>{{cite web| url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/court-filing-sheds-more-light-on-blankenship-campaigns/article_9b3993bf-b29c-5969-96f6-ba8f5d6aa2e1.html| title=Court filing sheds more light on Blankenship campaigns| agency=Associated Press| date=14 October 2017| publisher=Herald Dispatch| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref> That same year, Blankenship was criticized by Hillary Clinton's campaign after his appearance at her campaign stop in Williamson, West Virginia.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Clinton-responds-to-Don-Blankenship-showing-up-at-event-in-WVa-377969161.html| author=WSAZ News Staff| title=Blankenship issues statement after attending Clinton event| date=3 May 2016| publisher=WSAZ| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Climate change===\nBlankenship rejects the [[scientific consensus on climate change]]. In a speech at the Tug Valley Mining Institute, he said, \"I don't believe [[climate change]] is real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YEl7dF8N-ZU&e |title=Big Coal, Big Lies #1: Climate change does not exist |publisher=YouTube |date=December 9, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship reiterated his views on [[global warming]] in interviews with [[The Hill (newspaper)|''The Hill'']] and ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Snyder |first=Jim |url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/68031-qaa-with-don-blankenship-ceo-of-massey-energy-co |title=Q&A with Don Blankenship, CEO of Massey Energy Co. - The Hill&nbsp;\u2014 covering Congress, Politics, Political Campaigns and Capitol Hill |publisher=TheHill.com |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/09/28/massey-coal-environment-business-washington-blankenship.html |title=Seeing Red On Cap And Trade |magazine=Forbes.com |date=September 28, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an October 30, 2009, letter to the editor of ''[[The Charleston Gazette]]'', Blankenship denied that climate change, or global warming, exists, and said, \"Why should we trust a report by the United Nations? The United Nations includes countries like Venezuela, North Korea and Iran.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coalzoom.com/article.cfm?articleid=343 |title=Charleston Gazette \u2013 Letter to the Editor from Don Blankenship |publisher=Coal Zoom |date= |accessdate=October 9, 2012}}</ref> According to Blankenship, \"the environmental movement isn't a great cause, it's a great business\", and in addition to lying about the Upper Big Branch mine disaster, the government has also lied \"about the science of global warming.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.thenation.com/article/disgraced-coal-baron-don-blankenship-rebrands-libertarian-activist/| author=Lee Fang| title=Disgraced Coal Baron Don Blankenship Rebrands As A Libertarian Activist| date=28 July 2014| magazine=The Nation| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, at a Senate campaign town hall, Blankenship said that \"climate change is probably a fact\", but added that American-made climate change is not, arguing that China's increase in coal production is the reason.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.register-herald.com/news/former-massey-ceo-puts-ubb-blame-on-msha-outlines-positions/article_2520cd12-34ca-566c-aa1a-c7223efdc564.html| title=Former Massey CEO puts UBB blame on MSHA; outlines positions at campaign town hall| author=Jessica Farish| date=25 January 2018| newspaper=The Register-Herald| access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Mine safety===\nAt a 2009 Labor Day rally in West Virginia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://friendsofamericarally.com/ |title=Friends of America Rally |publisher=Friends of America Rally |date=September 7, 2009 |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> Blankenship said that federal and state mining regulators are ineffective at improving mine safety, and that the mining companies themselves are better suited to the task and should have less oversight,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climateprogress.org/2010/04/12/don-blankenship-mine-safety-regulators-silly-global-warming/ |title=Don Blankenship called safety regulators \"as silly as global warming\" \u00ab Climate Progress |publisher=Climateprogress.org |date=April 12, 2010 |accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> saying, \"Washington and state politicians have no idea how to improve miners' safety.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://theweek.com/articles/495341/massey-disaster-coal-baron-don-blankenship-blame| title=The Massey disaster: Is 'Coal Baron' Don Blankenship to blame?| author=The Week Staff| date=9 April 2010| magazine=The Week| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore and during his 2018 Senate campaign, Blankenship blamed the federal regulators of the [[Mine Safety and Health Administration|MSHA]] for the Upper Big Branch Disaster for directing airflow targets in the mine.<ref name=\"Dickerson\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theintelligencer.net/news/top-headlines/2018/03/senate-candidate-and-former-coal-ceo-don-blankenship-considers-conviction-a-badge-of-honor-in-west-virginia/ |title=Senate Candidate and Former Coal CEO Don Blankenship Blames MSHA, Considers Conviction A 'Badge of Honor' in West Virginia |publisher=The Intelligencer-Wheeling News-Register |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 United States Senate campaign===\nBlankenship entered the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] primary in the [[2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia|2018 United States Senate election in West Virginia,]] challenging incumbent Democratic U.S. Senator [[Joe Manchin]]. His television ads were aimed at \"getting the truth out\" about the Upper Big Branch explosion and \"exposing the government cover-up.\"<ref>{{cite magazine| url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/11/ex-con-coal-baron-don-blankenship-is-running-for-u-s-senate.html| title=Fresh Out of Prison, Reviled Coal Baron Don Blankenship Is Running for the U.S. Senate| author=Adam K. Raymond| date=29 November 2017| magazine=New York Magazine| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref> The ads further claimed Blankenship had documents showing that the MSHA Upper Big Branch internal report was falsified and that the company was forced by the MSHA to use a defective ventilation system.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/dec/11/don-blankenship/convicted-w-va-mining-ceo-falsely-says-government-/| title=Convicted mining CEO and GOP candidate says official papers reveal 'Obama's deadliest cover-up'| author=Jon Greenberg| date=11 December 2017| publisher=Politifact| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/26/us/don-blankenship-west-virginia-senate.html| title=Coal Country Divides Over an Unrepentant Boss's Senate Bid| author=Trip Gabriel| date=26 February 2018| newspaper=The New York Times| access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe also expressed a belief that Donald Trump's [[Executive Order 13767|proposed Mexico-United States border wall]] in conjunction ending sanctuary cities would help stop drug trafficking.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.wvnews.com/news/wvnews/don-blankenship-the-radical-republican-wants-to-be-wv-s/article_6f8ac8ea-5d6e-53b4-bca5-2fa1ca37566b.html| title=Don Blankenship, the 'radical' Republican, wants to be WV's conservative choice for Senate| author=Charles Young| date=25 March 2018| publisher=WVNews| access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship said he was \"Trumpier than Trump\" but that the establishment was misinforming him because they did not want him \"to be in the U.S. Senate and promote the president's agenda.\" The national Republican leadership and allied groups made statements and ran ads against Blankenship,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sanchez|first1=Luis|title=Blankenship: I'm Trumpier than Trump|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/386484-blankenship-im-trumpier-than-trump|website=The Hill|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> and the day before the Republican primary, Trump posted a tweet urging voters to vote for either of Blankenship's major primary opponents, [[Evan Jenkins (politician)|Evan Jenkins]] and [[Patrick Morrisey]], because Blankenship would not be competitive in the general election.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/07/politics/donald-trump-west-virginia-don-blankenship/index.html|title=Trump urges West Virginia voters to reject Blankenship|author1=Dan Merica |author2=Maegan Vazquez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Trump's tweet came in the wake of reporting that internal Republican polling had shown a surge in Blankenship's support among likely primary voters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/05/blankenship-polls-west-virginia-senate-primary-570752|title=Blankenship surging on eve of West Virginia Senate primary|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, whom Blankenship harshly criticized in his campaign, reportedly urged Trump to express opposition to Blankenship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/us/politics/don-blankenship-trump-west-virginia.html|title=Trump Weighs In on West Virginia Senate Race in Sign of Republican Anxiety|date=2018-05-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-05-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Republican primary campaign, Blankenship received criticism for calling McConnell's wife a \"[[Chinaman (term)|China person]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2018/05/04/don-blankenship-has-taken-opposition-to-political-correctness-to-a-new-extreme-and-thats-dangerous-for-the-gop/|title=Analysis {{!}} Don Blankenship has taken opposition to political correctness to a new extreme, and that's dangerous for the GOP|last=Scott|first=Eugene|date=4 May 2018|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/chinaperson-and-the-sanitization-of-a-racial-slur/558989/|title='Chinaperson' and the Sanitization of a Racial Slur|last=Zimmer|first=Ben|date=2018-04-26|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/02/politics/don-blankenship-defense-west-virginia-debate/index.html|title=GOP Senate candidate says 'wealthy Chinaperson' comment isn't racist|first=Maegan |last=Vazquez|work=CNN|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Patrick Morrisey]] won the primary, Blankenship reentered the race as the nominee of the West Virginia Constitution Party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=CARNEY|first1=JORDAIN|last2=KAMISAR|first2=BEN|title=Blankenship third-party bid worries Senate GOP|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/388706-blankenship-third-party-bid-worries-senate-gop|website=The Hill|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Mufson|first1=Steven|title=Spurned by Trump and GOP, coal baron Don Blankenship seeks a second chance in West Virginia|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/spurned-by-trump-and-gop-coal-baron-don-blankenship-seeks-a-second-chance-in-west-virginia/2018/05/22/27cd16a4-522d-11e8-9c91-7dab596e8252_story.html?noredirect=on|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his campaign he made a claim that the Upper Big Branch explosion was caused by the negligence of Mine Safety and Health Administration officials.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://grist.org/briefly/don-blankenship-fresh-outta-federal-prison-has-outlined-his-campaign-platform/| title=The 'Ship Has Sailed| author=Zoya Teirstein| date=26 January 2018| publisher=Grist| access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wvva.com/story/37001058/2017/12/Tuesday/don-blankenship-explains-decision-to-run-for-us-senate| title=Don Blankenship explains U.S. Senate run| date=5 December 2017| publisher=WVVA| access-date=11 April 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412001400/http://www.wvva.com/story/37001058/2017/12/Tuesday/don-blankenship-explains-decision-to-run-for-us-senate| archive-date=April 12, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2020 presidential campaign===\n[[File:Don Blankenship 20210 (75220642).jpg|thumb|Bankenship presidential campaign logo]]\nBlankenship launched his campaign for the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nomination in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] in October 2019 during a meeting of the Constitution Party national committee.<ref name=launchcampaign1>{{cite web| url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/10/20/don-blankenship-speaks-at-constitution-party-national-committee-meeting/|title=Don Blankenship declares for Constitution Party presidential nomination|website=Ballot Access News|date=October 20, 2019|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|accessdate=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBlankenship has two children.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |last1=Schelzig |first=Erik |url=http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929125507/http://www.wvec.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8E477907.html |archivedate=September 29, 2008 |title=Virginia News &#124; WVEC.com &#124; News for Hampton Roads, Virginia |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2016-12-30 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He was profiled in a 2005 [[West Virginia Public Broadcasting]] documentary, ''The Kingmaker''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=91CN9KsjSy8|title=The Kingmaker|via=YouTube|publisher=West Virginia Public Broadcasting}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===Deborah May===\nA former employee of Blankenship, Deborah May, similarly filed a lawsuit claiming that stress from personal abuse forced her to quit her job in November 2005. The lawsuit claimed that such comparatively minor mistakes as a wrong breakfast order from [[McDonald's]], misplaced ice cream in the freezer, and an improperly hung jacket in the closet caused difficulties with Blankenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/justices-hear-unemployment-appeal-from-ex-maid-to-blankenship/article_c784c684-15eb-5fe1-83a9-dc476b8f2b0c.html|title=Justices hear unemployment appeal from ex-maid to Blankenship|last=|first=|date=1 April 2008|website=The Herald-Dispatch|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> In June 2008, West Virginia's top court ruled that May was entitled to unemployment benefits because \"the unrefuted evidence\" showed that Blankenship \"physically grabbed\" the maid, threw food after she brought back the wrong fast-food order, and tore a tie rack and coat hanger out of a closet after she forgot to leave the hanger out for his coat. \"This shocking conduct\" showed May was in effect fired because she felt compelled to quit, the justices said.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/10_17/b4175048798671.htm |title=Massey Energy: The Accountant of Coal |last=Fisk |first=Margaret Cronin |last2= Sullivan |first2=Brian K. |date=April 15, 2010|magazine=BusinessWeek |access-date=April 15, 2010 |last3=Freifeld |first3=Karen }}</ref>\n\n===Upper Big Branch explosion===\n{{main|Upper Big Branch Mine disaster}}\nOn April 5, 2010 an [[Upper Big Branch Mine disaster|explosion at Massey's Upper Big Branch mine]] killed 29 miners. It was the worst U.S. coal mining disaster since 1970, when an explosion killed 38 in [[Hyden, Kentucky]]. [[NPR]] reported Massey executive Stanley Suboleski as saying that MSHA ordered airflow changes, made hours before the explosion, \"were changes the company opposed but complied with anyway.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126884971|title=Mine Probe Examines Airflow, Possible Tampering|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref> On April 12, [[New York State Comptroller]] [[Thomas DiNapoli]], trustee of the [[New York State Common Retirement Fund]] which held 303,550 shares of Massey stock, called for Blankenship to resign immediately. \"This tragedy was a failure both of risk management and effective board oversight. Blankenship must step down and make room for more responsible leadership at Massey.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Steve James |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63C2Q920100413 |title=Massey faces shareholder anger over mine disaster |work=Reuters |date= April 13, 2010|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> On April 22, Massey Energy's lead independent director [[Bobby Ray Inman|Bobby R. Inman]] announced that \"Blankenship has the full support and confidence of the Massey Energy Board of Directors.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/coal-boss-don-blankenship-full-support-massey-energy/story?id=10451791 |title=Coal Boss Don Blankenship Has Full Support of Massey Energy Board - ABC News |website=Abcnews.go.com |date=2010-04-22 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> On April 25, President [[Barack Obama]], Vice President [[Joe Biden]], and state officials paid tribute to the 29 coal miners at a memorial service in [[Beckley, West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2010/04/obama-eulogizes-29-miners-----dont-let-this-happen-again/1 |title=Obama eulogizes 29 W.Va. miners - 'Don't let this happen again' |website=Content.usatoday.com |date=2010-04-25 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref>\n\n\"Prosecutors said Massey manipulated the ventilation system during inspections of the Upper Big Branch mine to fool safety officials and disabled a methane monitor on a cutting machine a few months before the explosion on April 5, 2010....<ref>{{cite web|author=John Raby|url=http://www.rdmag.com/News/FeedsAP/2012/03/materials-ex-mine-leader-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-us-blast/ |title=Ex-mine leader pleads guilty in deadly US blast &#124; R&D Mag |publisher=Rdmag.com |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=September 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141203012554/http://www.rdmag.com/News/FeedsAP/2012/03/materials-ex-mine-leader-pleads-guilty-in-deadly-us-blast |archivedate=December 3, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref> In March 2013 Blankenship was directly implicated in conspiring to skirt safety regulations when a former Massey Energy official accused Blankenship of conspiring and plotting to hide safety violations from federal safety inspectors. The implication was that Blankenship would order his officials to warn mine operators when the federal inspectors were coming for \"surprise\" visits, and to quickly cover up any safety violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecontributor.com/don-blankenship-dark-lord-coal-country-implicated-upper-big-branch-mine-explosion-deaths|title=Coal Baron Don Blankenship Implicated In The Death Of 29 Miners|publisher=The Contributor|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBlankenship was convicted of a single misdemeanor charge of conspiring to violate federal mine safety standards and went on to serve a one-year prison sentence. He called himself a \"political prisoner\", feuded with United States Senator [[Joe Manchin]] and the [[Mine Safety and Health Administration]] (MSHA) over the explosion,<ref>{{cite news|last=Raby|first=John|date=May 11, 2017|title=Coal exec convicted in miner deaths is released from prison, immediately lashes out on Twitter|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-don-blankenship-mine-executive-20170511-story.html|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> considered running against Manchin for the Senate,<ref>{{cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Jeff|date=July 13, 2017|title=Blankenship: Senate run \"a possibility\"|work=MetroNews|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2017/07/13/blankenship-senate-run-a-possibility/|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> and called for a new investigation into the explosion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kercheval|first=Hoppy|date=September 8, 2017|title=My end of the week notes|work=MetroNews|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2017/09/08/my-end-of-the-week-notes/|access-date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> On May 25, 2017, he formally appealed his case to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]]. His petition argued that the U.S. District Court in Charleston and the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Virginia, \"both erred in rulings, and they claim Blankenship was a victim of politics.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511120601-blankenship-s-legal-team-files-appeal-petition-with-u-s-supreme-court|title=Blankenship's legal team files appeal petition with U.S. Supreme Court|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|date=2017-05-26|work=West Virginia Record|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Blankenship funded a television ad featuring the sister of one of the miners killed in the Upper Big Branch coal mine explosion. The sister, Gwen Thomas, asks in the ad \"if the United States Mine Safety and Health Administration insisted that changes be made which reduced Upper Big Branch's airflow before the explosion.\" She asks the government to publicly release the gas analyses taken after the explosion, and she asks for help from President Donald Trump and U.S. Senators Joe Manchin (D-WV) and Shelley Moore Capito (R-WV) in getting answers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511188274-sister-of-upper-big-branch-miner-featured-in-television-ad|title=Sister of Upper Big Branch miner featured in television ad|last=Asbury|first=Kyla|date=2017-08-18|work=West Virginia Record|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en}}</ref> The US Center for Disease Control's (CDC) National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) found that the initial explosion could have been prevented by MSHA forcing Massey to avoid a build up of gas, and that subsequent injury could have been prevented by forcing Massey to avoid build up of coal dust.<ref name=\":0\"/> The NIOSH's page on Mining, says that to avoid Methane buildup \"Large fans circulate air in mines to provide ventilation to the working areas.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/mining/features/coalmineexplosion.html|title=Coal Mine Explosion Prevention|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Blankenship for Senate released a statement outlining a finding of the Department of Justice's [[Office of Professional Responsibility]] (DOJ-OPR) which had investigated [[Booth Goodwin]] and [[Steve Ruby]], the prosecuting attorney's in Blankenship's federal trial. The DOJ-OPR found that both prosecutors were responsible for \"recklessly\" disregarding their discovery obligations. According to the release, at least 61 memoranda of witness interviews were not provided to Blankenship's defense team, and Blankenship's attorney believes these showed Blankenship had done nothing illegal.<ref name=\"Don Blankenship\"/>\n\n===Groundwater===\nBlankenship has been accused of withholding knowledge of pollution. According to accusations made in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', groundwater pollution from coal slurry injection by Massey Energy was contaminating wells around Blankenship's home. Blankenship had a water line built to his home from a nearby town. According to the accusation, Blankenship did not offer to provide uncontaminated water to any of his neighbors, and failed to inform them of any problem.<ref>[[Jeff Goodell|Goodell, Jeff]] (November 11, 2010). [https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/17390/236336?RS_show_page=4 Don Blankenship: The Dark Lord of Coal Country]. ''[[Rolling Stone]].'' Retrieved December 10, 2010</ref>\n\n===Campaign against Warren McGraw===\nIn 2004, Blankenship contributed $3 million to the \"And For The Sake of the Kids\" PAC, campaigning against the reelection of [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia|West Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice [[Warren McGraw]]. [[Brent Benjamin]] went on to defeat McGraw in the general election. Speaking about the election, Blankenship said, \"I helped defeat a judge who had released a pedophile to work in a local school, who had driven doctors out of state, and who had cost workers their jobs for thirty plus years. I think this effort helped unchain West Virginia's economy and benefited working families.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/10/idUS159711+10-Jun-2009+PRN20090610 |title=Don L. Blankenship Addresses the U.S. Supreme Court Ruling on Caperton v. A.T. Massey... |work=Reuters |date=June 10, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114051011/http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/10/idUS159711+10-Jun-2009+PRN20090610|archivedate=14 November 2012 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' called Blankenship's ads \"venomous.\"<ref name=\"usatoday1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/printedition/news/20090303/editorial03_st.art.htm |title=Mining case shows sooty side of big-money judicial elections |date=March 2, 2009 |access-date=April 6, 2010 |newspaper=USA TODAY}}</ref> According to a ''USA Today'' editorial dated March 3, 2009, Blankenship \"vividly illustrated how big money corrupts judicial elections. It puts justice up for sale to the highest bidder.\"<ref name=\"usatoday1\"/>\n\nNotably, Blankenship's coal company [[Massey Energy|Massey Coal]] had recently lost a civil case in West Virginia state court prior to the judicial campaign and had been ordered to pay a $50 million judgment. Blakenship's case was pending on appeal as he sponsored Brent Benjamin's campaign for a seat on the West Virginia Supreme Court. When the case was taken up on appeal, Benjamin was one of the judges in a position to decide the case. The plaintiff requested that Benjamin recuse himself owing to a conflict of interest stemming from Blakenship's contributions to his campaign, but he refused. Benjamin ultimately cast a decisive vote to vacate the lower court's judgment in a 3\u20132 decision. In [[Caperton v. A.T. Massey Coal Co.]], the Supreme Court ruled that Benjamin's refusal to recuse himself in light of such an obvious conflict of interest constituted a violation of the plaintiff's constitutional right to due process and remanded the case to the West Virginia Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2008/08-22|title=Caperton v. A. T. Massey Coal Co.|last=|first=|date=|website=Oyez|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n[[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] political journalist [[Michael Tomasky]], also a native West Virginian, claimed that Blankenship was \"famous in West Virginia as the man who successfully bought himself a State Supreme Court Justice in 2004 and then tried to buy himself the state legislature, failing spectacularly at the latter effort.\"<ref name=\"tomasky\">Tomasky, Michael, [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/21802 \"Night Comes to the Appalachians\"] ''[[New York Review of Books]]'', Volume 55, Number 14; September 25, 2008.</ref> In his 2008 book ''[[Coal River (book)|Coal River]]'', Michael Shnayerson reports that no such foundation was ever set up.<ref>Shnayerson, Michael (2008), ''Coal River'', New York, New York: [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]]</ref> Although Blankenship was the primary donor to \"And For the Sake of Kids,\" other groups, including Doctors for Justice, contributed over $1 million to ASK. Another group, Citizens for Quality Health Care, funded in part by the West Virginia Chamber of Commerce, spent over $350,000 to defeat McGraw.<ref>Nyden, Paul (January 7, 2005, Charleston Gazette), \"Coal, Doctor's Groups Donated to Anti-McGraw Effort.\"</ref> Meanwhile, several groups spent millions opposing Benjamin and supporting McGraw, including West Virginia Consumers for Justice and Hugh Caperton, CEO of Harmon Development Corporation.<ref>O'Brien, John (West Virginia Record January 24, 2008) \"Caperton was Anti-Benjamin from the Start.\"</ref> Blankenship is featured in [[Laurence Leamer]]'s 2013 book ''The Price of Justice: A True Story of Greed and Corruption''<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-8050-9471-8 |title=Nonfiction Book Review: The Price of Justice: A True Story of Two Lawyers' Epic Battle Against Corruption and Greed in Coal Country |author=Laurence Leamer |isbn=978-0-8050-9471-8 |website=Publishersweekly.com |date=2013-03-18 |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> and in Peter Galuszka's 2012 book ''Thunder on the Mountain: Death at Massey and the Dirty Secrets Behind Big Coal''.<ref>{{Cite book |title= Thunder on the Mountain: Death at Massey and the Dirty Secrets Behind Big Coal |last=Galuszka |first=Peter A. |date=2012-09-18 |isbn=978-1-250-00021-7 }}</ref>\n\n===Conflict of interest with Spike Maynard===\nOn January 15, 2008, photographs of Blankenship vacationing on the French Riviera with [[West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals|West Virginia Supreme Court]] Justice [[Spike Maynard]], while Massey had a case pending before that court, appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/15/us/15court.html | work=The New York Times | title=Motion Ties W. Virginia Justice to Coal Executive | first=Adam | last=Liptak | date=January 15, 2008}}</ref> On April 3, 2008, ''[[ABC News]]'' reported that Blankenship attacked an ''ABC News'' photographer at a Massey facility near [[Belfry, Kentucky]] as the photographer attempted to question Blankenship about the photos. \"If you're going to start taking pictures of me, you're liable to get shot!\" Blankenship stated in the video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/story?id=4582452&page=1 |title=Coal Boss: If You Take Photos, 'You're Liable to Get Shot' |publisher=ABC News |date=April 3, 2008 |accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> Maynard later lost his bid for reelection to the West Virginia Supreme Court in the primary election.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/15/us/15judge.html?pagewanted=print | work=The New York Times | title=West Virginia's Top Judge Loses His Re-election Bid | first=Ian | last=Urbina | date=May 15, 2008}}</ref> On February 14, 2009, Blankenship told ''The New York Times'', \"I've been around West Virginia long enough to know that politicians don't stay bought, particularly ones that are going to be in office for 12 years... So I would never go out and spend money to try to gain favor with a politician. Eliminating a bad politician makes sense. Electing somebody hoping he's going to be in your favor doesn't make any sense at all.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/15/washington/15scotus.html?ref=washington | work=The New York Times | title=Case May Alter Judge Elections Across Country | first=Adam | last=Liptak | date=February 15, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Comments on Mitch McConnell===\nIn April 2018, Blankenship released an ad in which he calls [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] \"cocaine Mitch\", urging potential voters to \"ditch\" McConnell.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Samuels|first1=Brett|title=Blankenship releases ad calling McConnell 'cocaine Mitch'|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/385574-blankenship-releases-ad-calling-mcconnell-cocaine-mitch|website=The Hill|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, he released another ad attacking McConnell, his wife, [[Elaine Chao]], and his in-laws as his \"[[Chinaman (term)|China family]]\", and again called McConnell \"cocaine Mitch\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/03/blankenship-mcconnell-china-568305 |title=Blankenship goes after McConnell's 'China family' in new ad |last=Isenstadt |first=Alex |date=May 3, 2018 |work=POLITICO |access-date=May 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Times McConnell\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/25/us/politics/don-blankenship-china-west-virginia.html|title=Don Blankenship, West Virginia Candidate, Lives Near Las Vegas and Mulled Chinese Citizenship|date=2018-04-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The premise of the moniker was that McConnell's father-in-law owns a shipping company that in 2014 was found to have {{Convert|90|lb}} of cocaine on one of its vessels set to leave Colombia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/5/7/17326708/cocaine-mitch-mcconnell-don-blankenship|title=Cocaine Mitch: Don Blankenship's factually dubious attack on McConnell, explained|publisher=Vox|first=Andrew|last=Prokop|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> The Colombian authorities did not accuse the company of conspiring to transport the cocaine, and the company was never investigated for the matter. McConnell, who has no role in the operation of his father-in-law's shipping business, was never suspected by any authorities of having any involvement in the incident. The ''Washington Post''<nowiki/>'s Fact Checker column investigated the \"cocaine Mitch\" claims and gave them a \"Four Pinocchios\" rating, concluding that \"Blankenship has no evidence to support his crude and incendiary attack.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2018/05/04/the-kooky-tale-of-cocaine-mitch/|title=Analysis {{!}} The kooky tale of 'Cocaine Mitch'|last=Rizzo|first=Salvador|date=2018-05-04|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> After Blankenship lost his primary race, an official campaign account for McConnell posted a photoshopped picture of McConnell surrounded by a cloud of cocaine dust with the accompanying text, \"Thanks for playing, Don.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Team_Mitch/status/994036999387537409|title=Thanks for playing, @DonBlankenship. #WVSen|website=Twitter|date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> The picture was based on promotional materials for the [[Netflix]] TV show ''[[Narcos]]''.\n\nWhen asked if Blankenship's rhetoric in the \"China Family\" political ad was racist, McConnell suggested that his answer would depend on the results of the Republican primary election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/05/mcconnell-blankenship-racist-west-virginia-republican-senate-primary.html|title=McConnell Won't Say if Blankenship Is Racist Until He Knows Election Result.|work=NYMag|first= Jonathan |last=Chait|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> When pressed on the ad's alleged racism, Blankenship said that his ad was not racist because the Chinese are not a race. He said, \"Races are Negro, White Caucasian, Hispanic, and Asian.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sfpathe/status/992202466648383488|title=Asked @DonBlankenship about his new ad being racist. Here's what he told me... #WVSEN|website=Twitter|date=May 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2018/05/don-blankenship-uses-negro-in-race-discussion-after-china-person-ad.html|title=Ex-Con West Virginia Senate Candidate Uses the Word \"Negro\" While Defending TV Ad About \"China People\"|last=Mathis-Lilley|first=Ben|work=Slate Magazine|access-date=2018-08-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{citation|last=Leamer|first=Laurence|title=The Price of Justice: A True Story of Greed and Corruption|place=New York|publisher=Times Books|isbn=9780805094718|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieCShJpT7y8C|date=May 7, 2013}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.votedonblankenship.com/ Vote on Blankenship, Official 2018 US Senate campaign website]\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blankenship, Don}}\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in the coal industry]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[