/suja.kapsi.fi/fmi-tilastot.php?taulukkomoodi=true| title = Rovaniemi extreme values | accessdate =18 May 2016 | publisher = [[FMI open data]]}}</ref>\n|width=77%\n}}\n\n[[File:rovaniemi1.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Rovaniemi in January 2004]]\n[[File:Santa Claus Village 20170201.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Santa Claus' Village]]\n[[File:Rovaniemi - Aurora Borealis.jpg|thumb|upright|Aurora Borealis]]\nThe average annual temperature in Rovaniemi is {{convert|0.9|C|F|1}}. Snow stays on the ground 175 days a year on average. The lowest temperature ever recorded at the airport is {{convert|&minus;38.1|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}, recorded on 28 January 1999. However, on the same day temperatures as cold as -47.5 C were recorded at nearby weather stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suja.kapsi.fi/asema-kuukausi.php?aika=1999-01-01&asema=101933|title=Rovaniemi Apukka - 01/1999 - S\u00e4\u00e4arkisto|website=suja.kapsi.fi|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\nThe highest temperature ever recorded is {{convert|32.2|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}, recorded on July 18, 2018 at the railway station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suja.kapsi.fi/asema-taulukko.php?asema=101928|title=Rovaniemi Railway station|website=Timeanddate.com|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that Rovaniemi experiences [[polar day]] between 7 June and 6 July (30 days) it does not experience [[polar night]]. However, the sun barely gets above the horizon in the winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeanddate.com/sun/finland/rovaniemi?month=7&year=2015|title=Sunrise and sunset times in Rovaniemi, July 2015|website=Timeanddate.com|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Twin cities==\nRovaniemi is [[Twin town|twinned]] with:<ref>{{Cite web |title=Yst\u00e4vyyskaupungit |publisher=City of Rovaniemi |access-date=22 August 2019 |url= https://www.rovaniemi.fi/fi/Palvelut/Kuntainfo/Ystavyyskaupungit |language=fi }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Ajka]], [[Hungary]]\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[Alanya]], [[Turkey]]\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Cadillac, Michigan]], [[United States]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Drvar]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n*{{flagicon|ISL}} [[Grindav\u00edk]], [[Iceland]]\n*{{flagicon|PRC}} [[Harbin]], [[China]]\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[St. Johann in Tirol]], [[Austria]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Kassel]], [[Germany]]\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Kiruna]], [[Sweden]]\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Murmansk]], [[Russia]]\n*{{flagicon|NOR}} [[Narvik]], [[Norway]]\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Neustrelitz]], [[Germany]]\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Olsztyn]], [[Poland]]\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Veszpr\u00e9m]], [[Hungary]]\n\n==Famous inhabitants==\n{{See also|Category:People from Rovaniemi}}\n\n*[[Jari Tervo]], author\n* [[Harri Olli]], [[Ski jumping|ski jumper]]\n* writer [[Timo K. Mukka]] died in Rovaniemi in 1974.\n* Snowboarder and 2005 Winter [[X Games]] gold medalist [[Antti Autti]] is a Rovaniemi native, and in April 2005 he received his own piece of land in the city for being named to the [[Finland at the 2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Finnish Olympic team]].\n* [[Tanja Poutiainen]] Alpine skier\n* World champion snowcross winner [[Janne Tapio]] is a Rovaniemi native.\n* [[Tomi Putaansuu]], better known as [[Mr. Lordi]] lead singer of the [[hard rock]] band and [[2006 Eurovision Song Contest]] winner [[Lordi]].\n* [[Progressive rock]] band [[Absoluuttinen Nollapiste]]\n* [[Antti Tuisku]], singer.\n* [[Santa Claus Village]] in Rovaniemi is said to be the residence of [[Father Christmas]]<!-- remove if nessecary -->.<ref name=\"northpole\"/><ref name=\"village\"/><ref name=\"office\"/>\n* The black metal band [[Beherit (band)|Beherit]] came from Rovaniemi.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe 1998 Spanish romantic film ''[[Lovers of the Arctic Circle]]'' ''(Los amantes del C\u00edrculo Polar)'', by director [[Julio Medem]], partly takes place in Rovaniemi.\n\nRovaniemi appears in the [[video game]] ''[[Tom Clancy's EndWar]]'' as a possible battlefield. In the game, Rovaniemi houses military facilities critical to a [[missile shield]] for a [[federal Europe|European Federation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://endwargame.us.ubi.com/locations.php |title=Locations |author=Ubisoft |publisher=[[Ubisoft]] |year=2008 |accessdate=1 April 2011|author-link=Ubisoft }}</ref>\n\nRovaniemi is a central scene in a documentary film ''[[Reindeerspotting]]''.\n\nTV-Star [[Bam Margera]] and his friends travelled to Rovaniemi in their film ''[[Bam Margera Presents: Where the \u266f$&% Is Santa?]]'' in order to find Santa Claus who is assumed to live in Rovaniemi.\n\nA version of the music video for [[Lordi]]'s song \"Hard Rock Hallelujah\" was filmed near Rovaniemi.<ref>{{cite video | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_M6px6Ynm90 | title=Hard Rock Hallelujah Special Edition | medium=YouTube video | location=Rovaniemi}}</ref>\n\nThe video for the [[Nightwish]] single \"[[The Islander (song)|The Islander]]\" was filmed in Rovaniemi by Stobe Harju.\n\nRovaniemi used to have the northernmost location of any [[McDonald's]] in the world<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/worlds-first-arctic-mcdonalds-opens-77808657.html|title=World's First Arctic McDonald's Opens|last=McDonald's|website=Prnewswire.com|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref> until the opening of a McDonald's in [[Murmansk]] in 2013, 23 years after it first opened in that country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barentsobserver.com/en/business/2013/07/queuing-worlds-northernmost-big-mac-02-07|title=Queuing up for world's northernmost Big Mac|website=Barentsobserver.com|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref> There are plenty of different [[restaurants]] to go for food in Rovaniemi from expensive to less expensive.\n\nRovaniemi appears as one location of [[Gavin Lyall]]'s 1963 book ''The Most Dangerous Game'' , a spy-thriller set in [[Lapland (Finland)|Lapland]] and the northern [[USSR]].\n\n==Sports==\nThe city is home to the football clubs [[Rovaniemen Palloseura]], or RoPS, part of the [[Veikkausliiga]], the Finnish premier division, and [[FC Santa Claus]], part of the [[Kakkonen|third division]]; to the [[ice hockey]] team [[Rovaniemen Kiekko]], or RoKi, whose home arena is [[Lappi Areena]] and which currently competes on [[Mestis]], the second-highest league in Finland; and to the volleyball team called Team Lakkap\u00e4\u00e4 (formerly [[Rovaniemen Santasport]] and [[Perungan Pojat]]), which plays in the [[Finland Volleyball League]] and won the national championship in 2003, 2007, 2008 and 2011.\n\nRovaniemi has hosted several international ski competition, including the [[FIS Nordic World Ski Championships 1984]], several [[FIS Nordic Combined World Cup]] and [[FIS Ski Jumping Continental Cup]] events, the [[FIS Nordic Junior World Ski Championships|2005 FIS Nordic Junior World Ski Championships]], the [[1970 Winter Universiade]] and the [[Transplant Games#Winter Editions|2008 Winter Transplant Games]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pilke House]]\n* [[University of the Arctic]]\n\n==References==\n=== Notes ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n* {{cite web |title=The dark, ruined city that became the home of Christmas |language=en |website=Quest's World of Wonder (CNN Travel) |format=Video and Text |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/rovaniemi-christmas/index.html}}\n* Rikkinen, K. ''A Geography of Finland''. Lahti: University of Helsinki (1992)\n* ''Rovaniemi: Arctic Circle \u2013 Finland''. Helsinki: Oy Sevenprint Ltd (1998)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Rovaniemi}}\n* [http://www.rovaniemi.fi/ City of Rovaniemi] \u2013 official website\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ll=66.50,25.70&spn=0.1,0.1&t=k Satellite view of Rovaniemi]\n\n{{Lapland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rovaniemi| ]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Finland]]\n[[Category:Christmas traditions]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|This article is about the city. For the soccer team known as Rovaniemi, see [[Rovaniemen Palloseura]].}}\n{{Infobox Finnish municipality\n|name                   = Rovaniemi\n|official_n